WEBVTT

00:11.891 --> 00:14.347
MAN: Ten-hut!

00:16.000 --> 00:22.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

01:14.161 --> 01:15.869
Be seated.

01:19.373 --> 01:21.496
Now, I want you to remember...

01:22.835 --> 01:26.703
...that no bastard ever won a war...

01:27.632 --> 01:30.038
...by dying for his country.

01:32.093 --> 01:33.587
He won it...

01:34.637 --> 01:39.430
...by making the other poor dumb
bastard die for his country.

01:41.563 --> 01:42.972
Men...

01:44.815 --> 01:47.899
...all this stuff you've heard
about America not wanting to fight...

01:48.151 --> 01:50.274
...wanting to stay out of the war...

01:50.779 --> 01:52.771
...is a lot of horse dung.

01:53.156 --> 01:54.401
Americans...

01:54.865 --> 01:57.273
...traditionally love to fight.

01:57.535 --> 02:02.779
All real Americans love
the sting of battle.

02:04.543 --> 02:06.334
When you were kids...

02:07.878 --> 02:10.913
...you all admired
the champion marble shooter...

02:11.131 --> 02:15.711
...the fastest runner, big-league
ball players, the toughest boxers.

02:16.429 --> 02:18.836
Americans love a winner...

02:19.347 --> 02:21.969
...and will not tolerate a loser.

02:22.392 --> 02:24.717
Americans play to win all the time.

02:24.978 --> 02:29.891
I wouldn't give a hoot in hell
for a man who lost and laughed.

02:30.735 --> 02:35.941
Thas why Americans have never lost
and will never lose a war...

02:36.740 --> 02:39.491
...because the very thought
of losing...

02:40.410 --> 02:43.031
...is hateful to Americans.

02:44.538 --> 02:45.736
Now...

02:46.833 --> 02:50.119
...an army is a team.

02:50.837 --> 02:53.459
It lives, eats, sleeps,
fights as a team.

02:53.715 --> 02:56.632
This individuality stuff
is a bunch of crap.

02:56.884 --> 02:59.968
The bilious bastards who wrote
that stuff about individuality...

03:00.220 --> 03:02.629
...for the Saturday Evening Post...

03:03.057 --> 03:07.636
...don't know anything more about real
battle than they do about fornicating.

03:10.230 --> 03:14.097
Now we have the finest food
and equipment...

03:15.194 --> 03:17.436
...the best spirit...

03:17.696 --> 03:20.153
...and the best men in the world.

03:21.575 --> 03:22.606
You know...

03:24.077 --> 03:28.490
...by God, I actually pity those poor
bastards we're going up against.

03:28.707 --> 03:29.952
By God, I do.

03:30.166 --> 03:33.083
We're not just going to shoot
the bastards...

03:33.585 --> 03:36.540
...we're going to cut out
their living guts...

03:36.798 --> 03:40.630
...and use them to grease
the treads of our tanks.

03:40.886 --> 03:45.796
We're going to murder those lousy
Hun bastards by the bushel.

03:46.682 --> 03:47.880
Now...

03:49.184 --> 03:51.011
...some of you boys...

03:51.395 --> 03:53.519
...I know are wondering...

03:54.399 --> 03:58.312
...whether or not you'll chicken out
under fire. Don't worry about it.

03:59.861 --> 04:01.854
I can assure you...

04:02.322 --> 04:04.564
...that you will all do your duty.

04:06.076 --> 04:07.904
The Nazis...

04:08.413 --> 04:10.404
...are the enemy.

04:10.706 --> 04:12.497
Wade into them!

04:12.958 --> 04:16.161
Spill their blood!
Shoot them in the belly!

04:17.128 --> 04:19.584
When you put your hand...

04:20.214 --> 04:22.502
...into a bunch of goo...

04:22.758 --> 04:26.459
...that a moment before was
your best frienďs face...

04:28.765 --> 04:30.425
...you'll know what to do.

04:32.811 --> 04:35.217
There's another thing
I want you to remember.

04:36.981 --> 04:41.690
I don't want to get any messages
saying we are "holding our position."

04:42.195 --> 04:45.646
We're not "holding" anything.
Let the Hun do that.

04:46.324 --> 04:50.486
We're advancing constantly. We're not
interested in holding on to anything...

04:50.702 --> 04:52.529
...except the enemy.

04:52.787 --> 04:56.536
We're going to hold on to him
by the nose and kick him in the ass.

04:56.792 --> 04:58.999
We're going to kick the hell
out of him all the time...

04:59.211 --> 05:02.959
...and we're going to go through him
like crap through a goose!

05:05.217 --> 05:06.497
Now...

05:09.262 --> 05:11.089
...there's one thing...

05:11.722 --> 05:15.471
...that you men will be able to say
when you get back home.

05:16.394 --> 05:18.601
And you may thank God for it.

05:20.357 --> 05:24.021
Thirty years from now when you're
sitting around your fireside...

05:24.235 --> 05:26.725
...with your grandson on your knee...

05:27.863 --> 05:29.274
...and he asks you:

05:29.531 --> 05:32.983
"What did you do in the great
World War II?"

05:34.120 --> 05:36.111
You won't have to say:

05:37.998 --> 05:39.242
"Well...

05:40.708 --> 05:43.627
...I shovelled shit in Louisiana."

05:46.716 --> 05:49.467
All right, now, you sons of bitches...

05:50.052 --> 05:51.961
...you know how I feel.

05:57.017 --> 05:59.056
I will be proud...

06:00.186 --> 06:04.266
...to lead you wonderful guys
into battle anytime...

06:05.983 --> 06:07.395
...anywhere.

06:10.822 --> 06:12.233
Thas all.

11:05.273 --> 11:07.681
The Arabs need food and clothing.

11:08.068 --> 11:11.021
They strip our dead before
we can even bury them.

11:11.320 --> 11:14.155
Looks like the reports were
pretty accurate.

11:16.909 --> 11:20.112
Sixty-one armored vehicles,
45 tons of ammunition...

11:20.371 --> 11:25.197
...twenty-five 40mm guns,
three self-propelled 105s.

11:25.792 --> 11:28.165
Not counting mortars, machine guns,
rifles...

11:28.420 --> 11:32.916
...pistols, telescopes, belt buckles,
GI socks.

11:34.468 --> 11:37.504
One thousand, eight hundred men.

12:34.108 --> 12:36.349
Our people salute you, general...

12:36.611 --> 12:40.692
...for your brilliant amphibious
landing on the continent of Africa...

12:40.907 --> 12:44.608
...and for your enlightened
administration of our country.

12:45.579 --> 12:47.155
I've enjoyed being here, Excellency.

12:47.413 --> 12:50.912
Naturally, I'd prefer to be in Tunisia
fighting the Germans.

13:03.928 --> 13:07.843
"The lions in their dens
tremble at his approach."

13:09.477 --> 13:11.552
I appreciate that, Excellency.

14:13.996 --> 14:15.788
Magnificent!

14:16.207 --> 14:17.915
I wish our troops looked that good.

14:51.116 --> 14:54.983
Tell me, general,
what do you think of Morocco?

14:55.203 --> 14:56.484
I love it, Excellency.

14:56.746 --> 15:01.242
Is a combination
of the Bible and Hollywood.

15:45.126 --> 15:48.163
BRADLEY: These men fight at Kasserine?
CARVER: Yes, sir.

15:48.379 --> 15:50.953
For the American Army to take
a licking like that...

15:51.173 --> 15:53.795
...the first time at bat
against the Germans...

15:58.056 --> 16:00.891
Up against Rommel, what we need
is the best tank man we've got.

16:01.101 --> 16:03.426
Somebody tough enough
to pull this outfit together.

16:04.937 --> 16:07.344
- Patton?
- Possibly.

16:08.273 --> 16:09.982
God help us.

18:03.135 --> 18:04.547
Lieutenant...

18:04.971 --> 18:07.046
...where is the duty officer?

18:07.264 --> 18:08.509
Sir...

18:08.724 --> 18:13.432
- He said he's caught at shaving.
- Why isn't he here on duty?

18:13.937 --> 18:15.597
Guess he needed a shave.

18:15.855 --> 18:19.140
We got a new commanding general
due today.

18:44.049 --> 18:47.085
MAN: Who the hell is kicking me
in the butt?

18:50.514 --> 18:52.305
Oh, sorry, sir.

18:52.558 --> 18:56.887
- What were you doing down there?
- Trying to get some sleep, sir.

18:57.104 --> 18:58.681
Well...

18:58.897 --> 18:59.928
Get back down there, son.

19:00.190 --> 19:03.393
You're the only son of a bitch here
who knows what he's trying to do.

19:03.651 --> 19:05.229
Yes, sir.

19:09.072 --> 19:12.738
PATTON: Brad, how the hell are you?
- Fine, George. Good to see you.

19:12.952 --> 19:15.788
We were all under the impression
you wouldn't be here until 0900.

19:16.039 --> 19:17.948
Yes, I gathered that.

19:18.583 --> 19:21.500
- You know my boy, Dick Jenson.
- Yes.

19:21.919 --> 19:23.995
Brad, tell me.

19:24.463 --> 19:27.833
- What are you doing here?
- Ike wanted a report on Kasserine.

19:28.051 --> 19:30.588
Meanwhile, I have to stay here
as an observer...

19:30.845 --> 19:32.801
...but I report directly to Ike.

19:33.013 --> 19:34.423
You're spying.

19:34.889 --> 19:37.345
Get me General Eisenhower's
headquarters.

19:38.685 --> 19:40.678
Tell me, Brad...

19:41.814 --> 19:44.602
...what happened at Kasserine?
I heard it was a shambles.

19:44.817 --> 19:47.354
Apparently, everything went wrong.

19:48.278 --> 19:52.276
We'd send over a 75mm shell,
the krauts would return an 88.

19:52.532 --> 19:54.655
Their tanks are diesels.

19:55.285 --> 19:59.448
Even when we managed to hit one
they kept on running. Our tanks...

20:00.915 --> 20:02.789
The men call them
"Purple Heart boxes."

20:03.042 --> 20:05.616
One hot piece of shrapnel
and the gasoline explodes.

20:05.879 --> 20:07.207
I warned them about the tank.

20:07.464 --> 20:10.132
I talked to one of the
soldiers about the half-tracks.

20:10.382 --> 20:13.881
I asked them if the machine-gun
bullets pierced the armor.

20:14.136 --> 20:15.761
And he said, "No, sir.

20:16.014 --> 20:19.263
They just come through one side
and rattle around a bit."

20:20.142 --> 20:23.475
I understand they had a little trouble
coordinating the air cover.

20:23.728 --> 20:25.139
The trouble was no air cover.

20:25.396 --> 20:28.849
- General Smith on the line, sir.
- Excuse me, Brad.

20:34.573 --> 20:35.948
Bedell?

20:36.241 --> 20:40.535
Listen, I'm calling about Bradley
and his job here.

20:41.246 --> 20:45.742
I need a good number-two man, I want
to make Brad my deputy commander.

20:47.084 --> 20:48.876
You clear it with Ike?

20:50.004 --> 20:51.795
All right, thanks, Bedell.

20:52.089 --> 20:55.424
Now you're not spying for Eisenhower
anymore, you're working for me.

20:56.136 --> 20:58.093
- Okay?
- Fine, okay.

20:58.638 --> 21:01.804
Dick. You got those stars?

21:02.516 --> 21:04.722
- Yes, sir.
- Les get them on.

21:16.904 --> 21:20.025
Whas the matter, Brad?
I've been nominated by the president.

21:20.576 --> 21:24.953
I know, but it doesn't become official
until is approved by the Senate.

21:25.414 --> 21:26.824
Well...

21:27.457 --> 21:30.162
...they have their schedule
and I have mine.

21:35.465 --> 21:36.578
George...

21:37.925 --> 21:41.010
...if you were named admiral
of the Turkish Navy...

21:41.220 --> 21:43.427
...I believe your aides could dip
into their haversacks...

21:43.682 --> 21:45.758
...and come up with the appropriate
badge of rank.

21:46.893 --> 21:50.806
Anyway, congratulations.
Premature congratulations.

21:52.064 --> 21:53.522
You know...

21:54.192 --> 21:57.976
I think those stars look better
on a green shirt.

21:58.237 --> 22:02.898
Did I ever tell you about the time I
designed a uniform for tank crewmen?

22:04.450 --> 22:08.152
It was green leather,
it had red stripes...

22:08.414 --> 22:12.198
...and sort of a row of brass buttons
down across here.

22:12.460 --> 22:15.413
And topped off
by a gold football helmet.

22:16.338 --> 22:18.959
The Army rejected it, of course.

22:19.215 --> 22:20.544
Goddamn, it was beautiful.

22:22.135 --> 22:24.377
Lloyd Fredendall is just leaving.

22:58.462 --> 23:03.586
George, there's one other thing I put
in my Kasserine report.

23:04.050 --> 23:06.755
Some of our boys
were just plain scared.

23:07.012 --> 23:08.636
Thas understandable.

23:08.888 --> 23:11.640
Even the best foxhound is gun-shy
the first time out.

23:11.891 --> 23:13.599
I can remember...

23:14.267 --> 23:17.388
...when nothing frightened me
as much as the idea of...

23:17.647 --> 23:19.105
...a bullet coming
straight for my nose.

23:19.357 --> 23:23.437
I don't know why, but the image of a
bullet coming right for my nose...

23:23.695 --> 23:25.984
...was more horrible
than any other possibility.

23:26.197 --> 23:29.648
Well, I can understand that,
with such a handsome nose.

23:31.827 --> 23:34.864
You want to know why this outfit
got the hell kicked out of it?

23:35.164 --> 23:37.157
Blind man could see it in a minute.

23:37.583 --> 23:40.334
They don't look like soldiers.
They don't act like soldiers.

23:40.585 --> 23:42.163
Why should they fight like soldiers?

23:42.420 --> 23:45.706
You're absolutely right.
The discipline's pretty poor.

23:46.550 --> 23:49.718
In about 15 minutes we're going
to start turning these boys...

23:49.971 --> 23:52.591
...into fanatics, razors.

23:52.806 --> 23:55.297
They'll lose their fear
of the Germans.

23:55.892 --> 23:58.846
I hope to God they never lose
their fear of me.

24:19.373 --> 24:22.209
Up bright and early, general?
Breakfast?

24:22.418 --> 24:24.541
Have all my officers
finished breakfast?

24:24.795 --> 24:26.835
We're open from 6 till 8.

24:27.089 --> 24:29.544
Most of the officers are
just coming in, sir.

24:29.799 --> 24:32.255
Please inform these officers
the mess hall is closed.

24:33.011 --> 24:35.253
But, sir! Is only a quarter to 8.

24:35.514 --> 24:40.177
From now on, you will open at 6
and no one will be admitted after 6: 15.

24:40.435 --> 24:41.846
Where are your leggings?

24:42.104 --> 24:45.852
Leggings? Well, hell, general, sir,
I'm a cook.

24:47.525 --> 24:49.103
You're a soldier.

24:50.069 --> 24:51.101
$20 fine.

24:56.075 --> 24:57.450
Gentlemen...

24:58.285 --> 25:00.362
...from this moment any man...

25:00.580 --> 25:03.700
...without leggings, without a helmet,
without a tie...

25:04.417 --> 25:07.785
Any man with unshined shoes
or soiled uniform...

25:10.047 --> 25:11.672
...is going to be skinned.

25:51.630 --> 25:55.626
This is a barracks.
Is not a bordello.

26:23.493 --> 26:25.532
- Good morning.
- Good morning, sir.

26:26.371 --> 26:27.402
Doctor.

26:27.664 --> 26:28.695
Sir.

26:28.957 --> 26:33.168
I understand you have two cases
of self-inflicted wounds.

26:33.419 --> 26:34.747
Yes, sir, we do.

26:35.004 --> 26:36.498
Get them out of here.

26:36.756 --> 26:39.129
One has developed a serious infection.

26:39.384 --> 26:42.551
I don't care if he dies,
just get him out of here.

26:42.804 --> 26:46.172
Doesn't belong in the same room
with men wounded in battle.

26:46.557 --> 26:49.308
- I'll see that they're moved.
- One more thing.

26:49.644 --> 26:52.847
There'll be no "battle fatigue."
Thas an order.

26:53.522 --> 26:56.392
Battle fatigue is a free ride
to the hospital.

26:56.649 --> 26:58.725
I'm not going to subsidize cowardice.

26:58.985 --> 27:00.148
Yes, sir.

27:00.361 --> 27:03.696
Doctor...
Where's your helmet?

27:05.158 --> 27:07.650
I don't wear a helmet
in the hospital.

27:08.537 --> 27:09.782
Start.

27:10.038 --> 27:13.039
I can't use my stethoscope
when I'm wearing my helmet.

27:15.752 --> 27:17.032
Well...

27:18.671 --> 27:22.039
...then cut two holes in your helmet
so that you can.

27:22.550 --> 27:25.800
And get those yellow-bellies
out of here, today.

27:34.311 --> 27:35.591
Hold it.

27:36.438 --> 27:37.718
Turn right, here.

27:37.981 --> 27:39.975
The battlefield is ahead.

27:40.193 --> 27:42.481
Don't argue.
I can smell a battlefield.

27:42.737 --> 27:44.361
He was out here yesterday.

27:44.613 --> 27:47.282
Is over there. Turn right, damn it.

28:29.699 --> 28:31.276
It was here.

28:34.494 --> 28:36.285
The battlefield was here.

28:45.340 --> 28:48.375
The Carthaginians
defending the city...

28:48.633 --> 28:51.919
...were attacked by three
Roman legions.

28:53.763 --> 28:57.974
They were brave, but they
couldn't hold. They were massacred.

29:00.477 --> 29:02.138
Arab women...

29:02.855 --> 29:06.723
...stripped them of their tunics
and their swords and lances.

29:08.403 --> 29:10.360
The soldiers lay naked in the sun...

29:13.866 --> 29:15.692
...2000 years ago.

29:20.081 --> 29:21.741
I was here.

29:27.003 --> 29:28.414
You don't believe me.

29:32.009 --> 29:33.836
You know what the poet said:

29:35.138 --> 29:37.378
"Through the travail of ages

29:38.932 --> 29:42.182
Is the pomp and toils of war

29:42.685 --> 29:47.181
Have I fought and strove and perished

29:47.690 --> 29:50.311
Countless times upon the star

29:55.115 --> 29:58.032
As if through a glass and darkly

29:59.119 --> 30:01.787
The age-old strife I see

30:03.121 --> 30:05.956
Where I fought in many guises
Many names

30:07.668 --> 30:09.293
But always me."

30:16.259 --> 30:18.251
You know who the poet was?

30:21.056 --> 30:22.219
Me.

32:31.265 --> 32:34.551
There's an opportunity
for us to mount an offensive.

32:34.811 --> 32:36.850
We've concentrated on the flank...

32:37.104 --> 32:39.013
...draw strength from the British.

32:39.231 --> 32:41.519
It appears now that we could...

32:41.733 --> 32:43.642
...split the African corridor.

32:43.901 --> 32:45.360
Drive through Rommel to the sea.

32:45.611 --> 32:48.649
I'm sorry, but that territory
has been reserved...

32:48.907 --> 32:51.150
...for General Bernard Law Montgomery.

32:51.411 --> 32:54.280
We're supposed to let him win this one
no matter what.

32:54.538 --> 32:56.993
They're entitled to have their hero.

32:57.248 --> 33:00.498
Montgomery did push Rommel
clear across North Africa.

33:00.877 --> 33:03.996
What about the Americans?
Don't they need a hero too?

33:04.921 --> 33:06.581
You have anybody in mind?

33:08.884 --> 33:12.171
Air Vice-Marshal Coningham
is here with General Buford.

33:12.430 --> 33:13.841
Excuse me, gentlemen...

33:14.057 --> 33:19.050
...while I ask our British friends
whas happened to our air cover.

33:20.312 --> 33:21.806
BRADLEY:
Harry.

33:22.064 --> 33:23.310
How are you?

33:23.524 --> 33:25.731
George. Good to see you.

33:27.278 --> 33:29.732
- You know Arthur Coningham.
- Sir Arthur.

33:29.988 --> 33:31.482
Delighted to see you.

33:32.699 --> 33:34.691
I've heard so much about you.

33:39.499 --> 33:44.290
Gentlemen, it appears there's been a
slight misunderstanding here...

33:44.544 --> 33:46.620
...and Ike thought we should fix it.

33:46.880 --> 33:48.919
No, no. No misunderstanding.

33:49.174 --> 33:52.009
We're supposed to have Allied
air cover and we don't.

33:52.260 --> 33:54.963
German planes are strafing my troops.

33:55.220 --> 33:59.384
If I may say so, general, I'm afraid
your operation reports are inaccurate.

33:59.642 --> 34:03.261
Report? Three days ago, the crowds
took off after my command car...

34:03.480 --> 34:05.223
...ran my ass into a ditch.

34:05.440 --> 34:08.605
My staff has assured me,
we have complete air supremacy...

34:08.859 --> 34:10.567
...everywhere in the Mediterranean.

34:10.777 --> 34:12.853
PATTON:
When I complained about air cover...

34:13.114 --> 34:15.900
...you said our troops
were not battleworthy.

34:16.158 --> 34:20.985
You spoke of the discredited practice
of using air force as an alibi...

34:21.246 --> 34:24.163
...for lack of success on the ground.

34:24.415 --> 34:28.117
I have to wet-nurse Montgomery,
I don't have to stand for that.

34:28.378 --> 34:31.996
I sincerely apologize for that remark,
whoever made it.

34:33.216 --> 34:35.789
And I promise you one thing, general:

34:36.011 --> 34:38.299
You will see no more German planes.

34:50.442 --> 34:53.645
We were discussing air supremacy,
Sir Arthur.

35:26.976 --> 35:28.257
Damn door won't open!

35:42.075 --> 35:44.281
By God, thas enough!

36:03.345 --> 36:05.468
Get that thing out of here!

36:06.390 --> 36:09.675
Come on, you bastards,
take a shot at me on the nose!

36:09.935 --> 36:14.431
Get back in here, George! We need
a corps commander, not a casualty.

36:41.215 --> 36:43.089
CONINGHAM:
How'd you manage to stage that?

36:44.427 --> 36:45.541
I don't know...

36:45.803 --> 36:48.838
...but if I could find
the Nazis flying those things...

36:49.055 --> 36:51.131
...I'd give them each a medal.

37:12.077 --> 37:15.114
PATTON: Can't get over how cold
it gets in the desert.

37:15.748 --> 37:17.623
Awfully cold, sir.

37:48.321 --> 37:50.610
PATTON: Rommel's out there somewhere,
waiting for me.

37:50.865 --> 37:52.241
JENSON:
Yes, sir.

37:54.202 --> 37:55.577
PATTON:
You know...

37:56.704 --> 38:00.997
...if I had my way, I'd send
that genius son of a bitch...

38:01.458 --> 38:04.958
...an engraved invitation
in iambic pentameter:

38:05.546 --> 38:09.082
A challenge in two stanzas
to meet me alone in the desert.

38:09.718 --> 38:11.212
I'll deliver it.

38:14.763 --> 38:17.468
Rommel in his tank and me in mine.

38:18.559 --> 38:22.058
We'd stop about 20 paces.
We'd get out, we'd shake hands...

38:22.897 --> 38:26.015
...then we'd button up and do battle,
just the two of us.

38:27.275 --> 38:30.394
That battle would decide
the outcome of the war.

38:31.321 --> 38:34.358
Is too bad jousting's
gone out of style.

38:35.451 --> 38:37.324
Is like your poetry, general.

38:37.577 --> 38:40.199
It isn't part of the 20th century.

38:41.039 --> 38:42.913
You're right, Dick.

38:44.459 --> 38:46.451
The world grew up.

38:47.545 --> 38:49.169
Hell of a shame.

38:51.882 --> 38:55.049
Dick, I want a 24-hour guard
put around this area.

38:55.303 --> 38:57.759
If we don't, the Arabs will dig
them up for their clothes.

38:58.014 --> 38:59.390
Yes, sir.

39:00.100 --> 39:03.966
Our graves aren't gonna disappear
like everybody else's who fought here.

39:04.478 --> 39:08.772
The Greeks, Romans, Carthaginians.

39:11.360 --> 39:13.980
God, how I hate the 20th century.

41:39.378 --> 41:40.623
General.

41:41.088 --> 41:42.332
General?

41:43.840 --> 41:46.081
We intercepted a German radio message.

41:46.342 --> 41:50.175
Rommel's 10th Panzer is going
to hit us near El Guettar.

41:56.102 --> 41:57.894
Rommel, huh?

43:48.669 --> 43:50.294
All my life...

43:52.299 --> 43:55.502
...I've wanted to lead a lot of men
in a desperate battle.

44:02.390 --> 44:04.265
Now I'm going to do it.

44:15.487 --> 44:16.566
Look.

44:51.855 --> 44:53.480
Battalion strength at least.

46:16.437 --> 46:18.976
They haven't spotted our positions yet.

46:19.649 --> 46:23.018
They'll get an education
in about 10 seconds.

46:23.278 --> 46:26.028
Wait till they get a dose of
that artillery fire.

46:41.085 --> 46:43.292
Commence firing.
Fire at will.

46:45.215 --> 46:49.426
Commence firing. Fire at will.
Commence firing. Fire at will.

47:49.485 --> 47:52.105
What a hell of a waste
of fine infantry.

48:10.172 --> 48:12.628
- Get General Bradley on the radio.
- Yes, sir.

48:31.317 --> 48:33.061
Sir, I can't raise him.

48:33.278 --> 48:36.812
Go tell him to hit them hard. Here's
where we hold them by the nose...

48:37.031 --> 48:38.905
...and kick them in the ass.
Go on.

49:54.147 --> 49:55.855
Put him in my car.

51:50.051 --> 51:51.331
Rommel...

51:52.762 --> 51:56.545
...you magnificent bastard.
I read your book!

52:21.497 --> 52:24.831
PATTON: Captain Richard N. Jenson
was a fine boy.

52:25.293 --> 52:28.876
Loyal, unselfish and efficient.

52:32.051 --> 52:34.292
I am terribly sorry.

52:43.478 --> 52:46.810
There are no coffins here
since there is no wood.

52:47.605 --> 52:50.560
We will have a trumpeter
and an honor guard...

52:50.818 --> 52:55.148
...but we will not fire the volleys as
people would think an air raid was on.

53:11.337 --> 53:15.798
I enclosed a lock of Dick's hair
in a letter to his mother.

53:17.970 --> 53:19.594
He was a fine man...

53:20.347 --> 53:21.890
...and a fine officer.

53:22.724 --> 53:24.966
And he had no vices.

53:33.651 --> 53:35.607
I shall miss him a lot.

53:45.830 --> 53:49.993
I can 't see the reason
such fine young men get killed.

53:51.418 --> 53:54.170
There are so many battles
yet to fight.

54:09.144 --> 54:12.643
NARRATOR: Battle-weary, but
victorious, American Gls and Tommies...

54:12.897 --> 54:16.349
...of the British 8th Army meet in
an Allied victory celebration...

54:16.609 --> 54:19.183
...at Wadi Akarit in North Africa.

54:19.404 --> 54:23.816
For the first time in this war,
Broadway and Piccadillyjoin hands.

54:27.912 --> 54:30.830
Meanwhile, General Montgomery,
hero of El Alamein...

54:31.041 --> 54:33.994
...continues to lead his
victorious British 8th Army...

54:34.252 --> 54:38.379
...in a relentless drive against
Rommel's vaunted Africa corps.

56:41.041 --> 56:44.326
General Bradley's done
a tremendous job with 2nd Corps.

56:44.586 --> 56:47.871
He's moved into Bizerte
and taken over 41,000 prisoners.

56:48.131 --> 56:49.541
Good. Very good.

56:49.799 --> 56:54.342
You're not surprised, are you?
After all, you trained that outfit.

56:59.100 --> 57:00.678
- Excuse me, general.
- Hm?

57:00.935 --> 57:05.596
This is interesting. We've discovered
Rommel wasn't present at El Guettar.

57:05.981 --> 57:08.519
- Who says so?
- G2, sir.

57:10.319 --> 57:14.151
When we took 10th Panzer,
Rommel was in Berlin with an earache?

57:14.365 --> 57:16.522
Severe nasal diphtheria, sir.

57:16.783 --> 57:19.487
Also, Hitler probably
retained Rommel in Berlin...

57:19.744 --> 57:22.069
...because things were going badly
for the Africa Corps.

57:22.330 --> 57:25.000
He didn't want his favorite general
to lose face.

57:25.208 --> 57:27.783
I'm my favorite general,
and I don't like to be told...

57:28.045 --> 57:31.662
...that some second-stringer
is up against me. Then I lose face.

57:39.222 --> 57:41.047
Who the hell are you, anyway?

57:41.431 --> 57:44.801
CARVER: General, this is Lieutenant
Colonel Codman. Your new aide.

57:45.019 --> 57:48.768
Codman. I pulled your name off
the list because I know your family.

57:49.024 --> 57:50.138
I'm glad you did, sir.

57:50.400 --> 57:54.064
Rommel is the best the krauts have,
and I kicked the hell out of him.

57:54.319 --> 57:57.237
Now my own G2 section is telling
me he wasn't even there.

57:57.489 --> 58:01.701
But, general, he undoubtedly
planned the German battle.

58:02.328 --> 58:07.119
If you defeat Rommel's plan, you've
defeated Rommel. Isn't that true?

58:08.583 --> 58:09.828
Codman...

58:11.962 --> 58:14.631
- Have a drink with me tonight.
- Yes, sir.

58:14.840 --> 58:17.758
I have a plan
for the invasion of Sicily.

58:18.009 --> 58:21.923
I want to make sure I get it approved.
You can help me.

58:22.138 --> 58:24.807
I want to give a dinner
for General Alexander.

58:25.016 --> 58:26.510
Get to him before Montgomery does.

58:26.768 --> 58:32.009
This will be strictly a formal affair,
Codman, but purely social.

58:32.356 --> 58:33.815
By that I mean...

58:34.024 --> 58:36.183
...purely political.
- Yes, sir.

58:36.444 --> 58:39.231
I want the finest food, the best wine
available. Everything, comme il faut.

59:08.892 --> 59:10.516
Thank you.

59:11.186 --> 59:14.021
George, this is really splendid wine.

59:14.230 --> 59:15.510
Thank you, Arthur.

59:18.609 --> 59:19.889
Thank you.

59:22.196 --> 59:26.574
Sir Harold, I think it was Alcibiades
in the Peloponnesian War...

59:26.785 --> 59:28.445
...415 B.C.

59:28.661 --> 59:32.610
He said, "If Syracuse falls, all
Sicily falls, and then Italy."

59:32.873 --> 59:36.372
He knew that Syracuse was the
jugular of the island.

59:36.626 --> 59:39.414
Old Alcibiades always went
for the throat.

59:39.672 --> 59:41.748
I propose to take Sicily
in the same way.

59:41.966 --> 59:45.168
- How's it going?
- The old man has them in his pocket.

59:48.846 --> 59:50.674
PATTON:
Now, according to my plan...

59:50.891 --> 59:53.927
...General Montgomery will land here.

59:55.146 --> 59:57.636
I'll hit the beaches here,
take Palermo.

59:57.856 --> 01:00:01.271
Monty will drive north on the coast,
I'll come due east...

01:00:01.526 --> 01:00:04.195
...take Messina and cut off
the German escape route.

01:00:04.529 --> 01:00:06.153
Yes...

01:00:06.364 --> 01:00:08.605
It looks like an interesting plan.

01:00:08.823 --> 01:00:12.276
Well, gentlemen,
to the conquest of Sicily.

01:00:13.162 --> 01:00:14.324
ALEXANDER:
To the conquest of Sicily.

01:00:14.956 --> 01:00:16.581
OFFICERS:
To Sicily!

01:00:17.375 --> 01:00:20.661
George, you'd have made a great
marshal for Napoleon...

01:00:20.920 --> 01:00:22.579
...if you'd lived in the 18th century.

01:00:22.921 --> 01:00:26.206
But I did, sir. I did.

01:01:02.751 --> 01:01:04.792
Morning. Is General Smith in?

01:01:05.046 --> 01:01:08.130
MAN: I believe he's in the lavatory.
- Thank you.

01:01:15.347 --> 01:01:18.017
- Ah, there you are, Bedell.
- Monty.

01:01:18.267 --> 01:01:22.181
Bedell, I've been giving a good bit of
thought to the Sicily operation.

01:01:22.438 --> 01:01:23.551
Yes?

01:01:24.522 --> 01:01:26.064
I assume we're alone.

01:01:26.274 --> 01:01:29.690
Georgie Patton has already
discussed his plan with Alexander.

01:01:29.945 --> 01:01:31.059
I realize that...

01:01:31.321 --> 01:01:35.235
...but I have an idea that his plan
may lead to an absolute disaster.

01:01:35.450 --> 01:01:36.695
Oh?

01:01:40.496 --> 01:01:41.576
Bedell, look.

01:01:41.789 --> 01:01:44.078
This is Sicily.

01:01:44.834 --> 01:01:47.750
Now then, according to Patton's plan...

01:01:47.961 --> 01:01:50.453
...I will attack Syracuse here.

01:01:50.673 --> 01:01:53.164
And he would attack Palermo up here.

01:01:53.426 --> 01:01:55.751
Now, obviously our forces would be
divided.

01:01:56.012 --> 01:01:58.717
And obviously, they
could be chopped up piecemeal.

01:01:58.973 --> 01:02:03.634
Now then, what I propose, and what
I shall insist on, by the way...

01:02:03.852 --> 01:02:05.097
...is this.

01:02:07.189 --> 01:02:10.107
I will land at Syracuse as planned.

01:02:10.317 --> 01:02:14.017
But the Americans-
The Americans will land here, at Gela.

01:02:14.237 --> 01:02:19.279
I will advance north to Messina,
the Americans protecting my flank.

01:02:19.493 --> 01:02:22.447
After all, Messina is the key.

01:02:22.705 --> 01:02:25.277
Is the reason for invading Sicily.

01:02:26.458 --> 01:02:29.031
I'll discuss your plan with Ike.

01:02:30.003 --> 01:02:32.790
I'm sure he'll give it
serious consideration.

01:02:38.009 --> 01:02:39.385
- Amusing, isn't it?
- What?

01:02:39.637 --> 01:02:41.345
That the plans for the
invasion of Sicily...

01:02:41.597 --> 01:02:44.468
...should have been put forward
in an Algerian lavatory.

01:02:44.893 --> 01:02:48.226
George, I have bad news for you
about your Sicily plan.

01:02:48.479 --> 01:02:50.518
Ike has turned it down.

01:02:50.897 --> 01:02:55.311
Since the Italians will be defending
their native soil for the first time...

01:02:55.528 --> 01:03:00.106
...and the German resistance is
stiffening, we shouldn't be divided.

01:03:00.949 --> 01:03:04.863
- Well, where do my people land then?
- In the Gulf of Gela.

01:03:05.077 --> 01:03:06.702
There's nothing there
but a beach.

01:03:06.954 --> 01:03:10.953
Yes, but it puts you in a good
position to support Montgomery.

01:03:12.044 --> 01:03:13.751
Where does Montgomery land?

01:03:14.004 --> 01:03:18.250
He'll land in Syracuse and drive north
to Catania. Possibly even Messina.

01:03:18.675 --> 01:03:21.794
And you'll be alongside,
protecting his left.

01:03:22.303 --> 01:03:23.466
I see.

01:03:25.389 --> 01:03:29.802
In other words, we get the burden again
while good old Monty gets the glory.

01:03:30.060 --> 01:03:32.848
Ike had to consider all points of view.

01:03:33.064 --> 01:03:36.398
He made his decision not as an
American, but as an Ally.

01:03:37.360 --> 01:03:40.775
Had it been the other way around,
I assure you, Monty would protest.

01:03:42.113 --> 01:03:43.276
No...

01:03:44.784 --> 01:03:47.025
...I've been in the Army 30 years.

01:03:47.411 --> 01:03:51.823
When I get an order, I say, "Yes, sir."
And I do my best to carry it out.

01:03:55.918 --> 01:04:00.047
This is what happens when your
commander stops being an American...

01:04:00.466 --> 01:04:02.458
...and starts being an Ally.

01:05:13.536 --> 01:05:15.778
I don't think I've made
myself clear, sir.

01:05:16.039 --> 01:05:19.620
Is true, Montgomery met the
toughest resistance there at Catania.

01:05:19.833 --> 01:05:20.782
However, if we're-

01:05:21.042 --> 01:05:22.454
Perfectly clear.

01:05:22.712 --> 01:05:26.756
Old Monty is as stuck
as a bug on flypaper.

01:05:27.591 --> 01:05:29.713
But this order from
General Alexander...

01:05:29.967 --> 01:05:33.799
...directing you to turn over the
Vizzini-Caltagirone road to Montgomery.

01:05:34.388 --> 01:05:37.556
Well, then, old Bradley will have to
slug- slug, mind you...

01:05:37.767 --> 01:05:42.560
...his way up center of the island over
those tough mountain roads, won't he?

01:05:42.814 --> 01:05:44.012
Yes, sir.

01:05:44.440 --> 01:05:46.314
Messina, Bell.

01:05:46.859 --> 01:05:47.974
Messina...

01:05:49.028 --> 01:05:52.064
...is the heart of it. If they'd
followed my plan, I'd be there by now.

01:05:52.281 --> 01:05:55.697
I'd cut off the retreat of every
German on this island!

01:05:56.744 --> 01:05:58.701
Now, you know what I'm gonna do?

01:05:58.954 --> 01:06:00.284
I'm gonna go to Palermo.

01:06:00.540 --> 01:06:04.538
I'm gonna beat that limey at Messina
if is the last thing I ever do!

01:06:04.752 --> 01:06:09.247
Hey, whas all this talk about taking
the Vizzini road away from 2nd Corps?

01:06:12.635 --> 01:06:15.505
General Alexander's orders.
Road goes to Montgomery.

01:06:15.763 --> 01:06:18.431
Now, that road was assigned to me.

01:06:19.182 --> 01:06:21.969
How can I get north without it?
You know the terrain there.

01:06:22.184 --> 01:06:26.349
I'm sorry, Brad. But Monty's run
into tough opposition. Very tough.

01:06:28.859 --> 01:06:32.523
You wouldn't be taking advantage of
this situation, would you?

01:06:32.779 --> 01:06:34.273
I don't know what you're talking about.

01:06:34.531 --> 01:06:37.697
Without that road, your army,
except for my 2nd Corps...

01:06:37.909 --> 01:06:39.284
...would be out of a job.

01:06:39.827 --> 01:06:41.903
Free for you to go into Palermo.

01:06:42.163 --> 01:06:44.285
Who said anything about Palermo?

01:06:45.749 --> 01:06:47.623
I can read a map.

01:06:48.670 --> 01:06:51.161
Does Alexander know
you've pushed out this far?

01:06:51.422 --> 01:06:54.092
Thas a reconnaissance in force.

01:06:57.052 --> 01:06:58.250
George...

01:07:00.180 --> 01:07:02.506
...are you saying I've got to slug
it out in those mountains...

01:07:02.767 --> 01:07:04.925
...with heavy resistance?

01:07:05.477 --> 01:07:08.477
Just so you can make
a bigger splash than Monty?

01:07:09.063 --> 01:07:10.344
General...

01:07:11.274 --> 01:07:13.397
...I just follow my orders.

01:07:13.652 --> 01:07:16.190
Like the simple old soldier I am.

01:07:17.155 --> 01:07:18.698
General Bradley.

01:07:19.783 --> 01:07:22.867
Sir, General Alexander has heard
we're moving west.

01:07:23.119 --> 01:07:27.448
He says here, "Stop immediately.
Go no farther than Agrigento.

01:07:27.707 --> 01:07:30.577
Repeat. Stop, immediately."

01:07:31.335 --> 01:07:33.493
Thas what you think it says.

01:07:33.879 --> 01:07:36.833
I think it was garbled
in transmission.

01:07:37.091 --> 01:07:39.629
Ask them to re-transmit the message.

01:07:39.886 --> 01:07:42.044
Thall take half a day at least.

01:07:42.263 --> 01:07:43.342
Yes, sir.

01:07:47.601 --> 01:07:49.143
Now, Brad.

01:07:51.856 --> 01:07:53.314
Where were we?

01:07:55.192 --> 01:07:57.896
We were talking about a simple...

01:07:58.111 --> 01:07:59.770
...old soldier.

01:08:30.225 --> 01:08:31.685
Look at that, gentlemen.

01:08:34.020 --> 01:08:35.846
Compared to war...

01:08:36.314 --> 01:08:39.600
...all other forms of human endeavor
shrink to insignificance.

01:08:40.444 --> 01:08:42.733
Les go, sergeant.
Move out!

01:09:32.411 --> 01:09:34.450
Give me that helmet.

01:09:37.038 --> 01:09:38.831
Come on, les get out of here!

01:09:51.136 --> 01:09:53.426
What silly son of a bitch
is in charge of this operation?

01:09:53.680 --> 01:09:56.350
I don't know, but they
ought to hang him.

01:10:08.446 --> 01:10:09.857
PATTON:
Afternoon, Padre.

01:10:10.073 --> 01:10:12.693
PADRE: These men are here from the
States, looking over our program...

01:10:12.949 --> 01:10:14.741
...for the spiritual welfare
of the men.

01:10:14.951 --> 01:10:16.659
We'll take you right into Palermo.

01:10:16.911 --> 01:10:19.071
Col. David toured us around
your quarters...

01:10:19.331 --> 01:10:24.039
...and I saw a Bible by your bed.
Do you actually find time to read it?

01:10:24.752 --> 01:10:26.081
I sure do.

01:10:26.337 --> 01:10:28.246
Every goddamn day.

01:10:51.195 --> 01:10:53.686
Sir, Patton's taken Palermo!

01:10:54.866 --> 01:10:55.696
Damn!

01:11:14.050 --> 01:11:16.754
Palermo's the most conquered city
in history.

01:11:17.011 --> 01:11:18.920
First the Phoenicians...

01:11:19.348 --> 01:11:22.882
...the Romans,
Carthaginians, Byzantines.

01:11:23.143 --> 01:11:24.887
Then came the Arabs...

01:11:25.146 --> 01:11:27.682
...Spaniards, Neapolitans.

01:11:27.897 --> 01:11:29.356
Now comes...

01:11:29.566 --> 01:11:31.439
...the American Army.

01:11:41.619 --> 01:11:43.611
This is from General Alexander, sir...

01:11:43.872 --> 01:11:47.075
...reminding you that you are
not to take Palermo.

01:11:47.667 --> 01:11:49.790
Send him a message, Cod.

01:11:50.085 --> 01:11:52.327
Ask him if he
wants me to give it back.

01:12:38.800 --> 01:12:40.459
PATTON: Let me ask you a question
for a change.

01:12:40.717 --> 01:12:42.626
You've just come from Washington.

01:12:42.928 --> 01:12:45.384
How do they feel about our boys
taking Palermo?

01:12:45.639 --> 01:12:49.851
The general impression is, your army
barreled through token resistance...

01:12:50.102 --> 01:12:52.473
...while Montgomery faced the brunt
of the fighting.

01:12:52.728 --> 01:12:55.480
Don't they know we took on
the Hermann Göring division?

01:12:55.731 --> 01:12:57.142
Toughest outfit in the German Army.

01:12:57.400 --> 01:12:59.477
The people at home
are interested in you.

01:12:59.694 --> 01:13:01.937
They're curious about your
pearl-handle revolvers.

01:13:02.156 --> 01:13:05.275
They're ivory. Only a pimp
from a New Orleans whorehouse...

01:13:05.533 --> 01:13:07.158
...would carry a pearl handle.

01:13:07.368 --> 01:13:09.028
What about your language?

01:13:09.287 --> 01:13:12.371
When I want it to stick,
I give it to them loud and dirty.

01:13:12.623 --> 01:13:14.450
What do your troops feel about that?

01:13:14.709 --> 01:13:18.076
I don't want these men to love me.
I want them to fight for me.

01:13:18.462 --> 01:13:22.591
Ernie Pyle says you have a secret
weapon here: General Bradley.

01:13:22.801 --> 01:13:24.674
Ernie calls him "The GI General."

01:13:24.886 --> 01:13:28.006
Omar Bradley is no secret.
He's a damn fine commander.

01:13:28.264 --> 01:13:30.505
MAN:
Whas your feeling about Montgomery?

01:13:30.765 --> 01:13:32.924
PATTON:
He's the best general the English have.

01:13:33.184 --> 01:13:36.768
He seems more concerned with not
losing than he does about winning.

01:13:37.022 --> 01:13:40.107
He's not aggressive enough,
is that correct?

01:13:40.650 --> 01:13:43.437
Look, I've been getting into
a lot of trouble lately.

01:13:43.694 --> 01:13:46.648
Yesterday, the office told me
that my Italian prisoners...

01:13:46.907 --> 01:13:48.698
...didn't have enough latrine.

01:13:49.284 --> 01:13:52.321
They didn't know what a
latrine was till I showed them.

01:13:52.580 --> 01:13:55.948
If I've said anything too critical
of my British colleague...

01:13:56.165 --> 01:13:57.494
...les forget about it.

01:13:57.750 --> 01:14:00.751
I will tell you one thing, though.
Off the record.

01:14:01.546 --> 01:14:03.253
I'm gonna beat that...

01:14:03.464 --> 01:14:05.337
...gentleman to Messina.

01:14:13.558 --> 01:14:17.009
Ah, Freddie. Do you realize what
this madman Patton is saying?

01:14:17.270 --> 01:14:19.510
He's going to save our skins
by taking Messina.

01:14:19.771 --> 01:14:21.811
This report might interest you.

01:14:22.065 --> 01:14:25.649
Here I am in these bloody marshes,
fighting malaria and Germans...

01:14:25.903 --> 01:14:29.236
...while he's taking Palermo
and getting all the glory.

01:14:31.074 --> 01:14:32.236
Well!

01:14:32.450 --> 01:14:36.199
Now he's up against three good
German divisions and he's stuck.

01:14:36.455 --> 01:14:38.198
He's not going to get Messina.

01:14:38.456 --> 01:14:41.826
Thas reserved for the
British 8th Army and me.

01:14:48.383 --> 01:14:52.676
Is time for a move, Lucian. Terry
Allen's 1 st Division is bogged down.

01:14:52.929 --> 01:14:54.552
You're bogged down too.

01:14:54.804 --> 01:14:58.091
What we need is another end run
just to break things loose.

01:14:59.601 --> 01:15:02.687
- Lucian. How's my fighter?
- Fine, George.

01:15:03.022 --> 01:15:07.268
Come in, come in. We need another
one of your amphibious specialties.

01:15:10.487 --> 01:15:14.651
Lucian, I want you to send a
reinforced battalion by sea...

01:15:14.909 --> 01:15:18.324
...to make a landing up here at Brolo
behind the kraut lines.

01:15:18.579 --> 01:15:20.950
You want me to do a land-based attack.

01:15:21.205 --> 01:15:24.491
Right. I want a coordinated
attack the morning of the 11 th.

01:15:24.750 --> 01:15:26.958
I don't think we can make it
by the 11 th.

01:15:27.212 --> 01:15:32.087
- Hell, is only 15, 20 miles.
- My boys have been dying for yards.

01:15:33.092 --> 01:15:34.290
Hm.

01:15:34.719 --> 01:15:37.636
Maybe you better kick a few butts
if you have to.

01:15:38.639 --> 01:15:41.593
I recommended you for your DSM
in your last promotion.

01:15:41.809 --> 01:15:44.299
I know what you can do when
you put your mind to it.

01:15:44.894 --> 01:15:46.603
Excuse me, sir.

01:15:47.898 --> 01:15:50.983
I'm sorry, but I can't
do the impossible.

01:15:52.237 --> 01:15:55.984
You're too old an athlete to think
you can postpone a scheduled match.

01:15:56.198 --> 01:15:59.780
You're an old athlete yourself.
You know matches are postponed.

01:16:00.035 --> 01:16:04.329
If we can't back Lucian up by land,
our end run could be a disaster.

01:16:04.540 --> 01:16:08.488
Those men might get caught
on the beach and cut to pieces.

01:16:08.710 --> 01:16:11.283
- Whas the matter?
BRADLEY: All we're saying is...

01:16:11.504 --> 01:16:14.173
...not to rush in until we're ready.

01:16:14.423 --> 01:16:16.216
Give him an extra day.

01:16:16.426 --> 01:16:17.837
Just one more day.

01:16:18.219 --> 01:16:20.178
The landing is on.

01:16:20.638 --> 01:16:21.836
We're going to Messina.

01:16:22.223 --> 01:16:25.592
We're going to get there before
Montgomery does.

01:16:25.810 --> 01:16:30.306
- Whas so important about that?
- General Truscott...

01:16:30.565 --> 01:16:34.264
...if your conscience won't permit
you to conduct this operation...

01:16:34.484 --> 01:16:36.145
...I'll find somebody who can.

01:16:36.362 --> 01:16:41.439
General, is your privilege to
relieve me anytime you want to.

01:16:41.659 --> 01:16:44.779
This match will not be postponed.

01:16:46.997 --> 01:16:48.195
Any questions?

01:16:54.004 --> 01:16:55.167
No, sir.

01:16:55.589 --> 01:16:58.126
You're a very good man, Lucian.

01:16:58.382 --> 01:17:01.253
You want to guard against
being too conservative.

01:17:01.469 --> 01:17:03.711
Remember what
Frederick the Great said:

01:17:03.930 --> 01:17:08.593
"L 'audace, I'audace!
Toujours I'audace!"

01:17:10.603 --> 01:17:12.512
Go on, have a drink.

01:17:13.690 --> 01:17:18.766
Excuse me, sir, I won't be drinking
for the next couple of days.

01:17:22.405 --> 01:17:25.905
If anything happens to those men,
I'd like to be there with them.

01:17:28.913 --> 01:17:31.285
You're not going, so forget about it.

01:17:32.959 --> 01:17:35.449
You believe Truscos right?

01:17:36.294 --> 01:17:37.575
No.

01:17:39.130 --> 01:17:41.836
But you're gambling
with those boys' lives...

01:17:42.051 --> 01:17:44.624
...just to beat Montgomery
into Messina.

01:17:45.804 --> 01:17:49.219
If you pull it off, you're a hero,
but if you don't...

01:17:50.099 --> 01:17:54.014
What happens to them?
The ordinary combat soldier.

01:17:54.813 --> 01:17:58.811
He doesn't share in your dreams
of glory, he's stuck here.

01:17:59.567 --> 01:18:04.443
He's living out every day, day-to-day,
with death tugging at his elbow.

01:18:08.326 --> 01:18:11.528
There's one big difference
between you and me, George.

01:18:13.414 --> 01:18:16.331
I do this job because I've been
trained to do it.

01:18:17.084 --> 01:18:18.828
You do it because...

01:18:20.964 --> 01:18:22.588
...you love it.

01:18:38.688 --> 01:18:41.475
The men on the beach are
catching hell, general.

01:18:41.732 --> 01:18:45.351
The men are doing their best.
We have no replacements.

01:18:45.570 --> 01:18:48.109
I can't break through to the coast.

01:18:48.364 --> 01:18:50.322
I'm going down there myself.

01:19:05.381 --> 01:19:06.792
PATTON:
Colonel!

01:19:07.884 --> 01:19:09.627
How did he get over there?

01:19:09.928 --> 01:19:11.801
PATTON:
What the hell are you waiting for?

01:19:12.013 --> 01:19:15.546
Looking for a place to ford, general.

01:19:15.765 --> 01:19:17.758
I sent a patrol to reconnoiter.

01:19:17.976 --> 01:19:22.437
PATTON: I've done that. Down there
this sewer's no more than 3 feet deep.

01:19:22.648 --> 01:19:25.767
Get that outfit cranked up
or you'll be out of a job!

01:19:27.860 --> 01:19:30.980
- And put that helmet on.
- Yes, sir.

01:19:46.045 --> 01:19:48.168
Move it! Les go!

01:19:58.057 --> 01:20:01.557
- Whas holding up this column?
- I don't know, sir.

01:20:01.769 --> 01:20:02.883
Planes!

01:20:07.273 --> 01:20:08.733
Come on, move it!

01:20:32.048 --> 01:20:33.542
Pull up over there.

01:20:39.846 --> 01:20:41.471
- Come on.
- Whas going on here?

01:20:41.682 --> 01:20:42.595
Sir, these mules-

01:20:42.808 --> 01:20:43.839
Jackasses!

01:20:44.226 --> 01:20:48.688
You let a column get stalled and
strafed on account of two jackasses?!

01:20:53.068 --> 01:20:54.811
No. No.

01:21:02.536 --> 01:21:05.452
Now, dump them over the side
and clear this bridge!

01:21:52.668 --> 01:21:55.537
We're pinned down because
we can't get air support!

01:21:55.795 --> 01:21:57.871
Nobody's getting any air support!

01:21:58.089 --> 01:22:01.293
Put fire into this battalion,
or I'll get somebody who can.

01:22:01.509 --> 01:22:02.790
Major!

01:22:03.262 --> 01:22:04.922
- You the executive officer here?
- Yes, sir.

01:22:05.138 --> 01:22:06.466
- Your name?
- Walker.

01:22:06.681 --> 01:22:08.389
You're now commanding officer.

01:22:08.600 --> 01:22:11.007
You've got 4 hours to break through
that beachhead.

01:22:11.227 --> 01:22:13.220
If you don't make it, I'll fire you.

01:22:22.400 --> 01:22:27.239
50,000 men on this island would
like to shoot that son of a bitch.

01:23:02.481 --> 01:23:05.820
Please take me home.
Take me home.

01:23:06.694 --> 01:23:09.364
Please take me home.
Take me home.

01:23:33.179 --> 01:23:38.310
- There he goes, "Old Blood and Guts."
- Yeah, our blood. His guts.

01:23:45.694 --> 01:23:47.111
Hi, how are you, son?

01:23:54.993 --> 01:23:56.786
Where are you from, Gomez?

01:23:58.163 --> 01:24:00.080
California, sir.

01:24:00.291 --> 01:24:01.918
Me too.

01:24:02.376 --> 01:24:06.295
- Where were you hit?
- In the chest, sir.

01:24:06.880 --> 01:24:08.174
Well...

01:24:08.633 --> 01:24:13.762
...this might be interesting to you.
The last German I saw had no chest.

01:24:14.263 --> 01:24:16.097
Didn't have any head either.

01:24:18.183 --> 01:24:20.060
You get well quickly, son.

01:26:16.885 --> 01:26:18.511
Whas the matter with you?

01:26:22.473 --> 01:26:25.393
I guess I just can't take it, sir.

01:26:29.397 --> 01:26:30.815
What did you say?

01:26:34.318 --> 01:26:36.237
Is my nerves, sir.

01:26:37.739 --> 01:26:40.617
I just can't stand
the shelling anymore.

01:26:43.159 --> 01:26:44.995
Your nerves?

01:26:46.831 --> 01:26:49.793
Hell, you're just a goddamn coward.

01:26:52.253 --> 01:26:53.547
Shut up!

01:26:55.798 --> 01:26:58.133
I won't have
a yellow bastard crying...

01:26:58.550 --> 01:27:00.845
...in front of these
brave, wounded men.

01:27:04.223 --> 01:27:05.641
Shut up!

01:27:08.394 --> 01:27:12.105
Don't admit this yellow bastard.
Nothing wrong with him.

01:27:12.356 --> 01:27:17.069
I won't have sons of bitches afraid to
fight stink up this place of honor.

01:27:17.654 --> 01:27:20.239
You're going back to the front,
my friend.

01:27:20.447 --> 01:27:25.119
You may get shot, you may get killed,
but you're going up to the fighting.

01:27:25.704 --> 01:27:29.247
Either that or I'll stand you up
in front of a firing squad.

01:27:29.665 --> 01:27:33.794
I should shoot you myself,
you bastard! Get him out of here!

01:27:36.088 --> 01:27:37.549
Send him up to the front!

01:27:37.799 --> 01:27:41.928
You hear me? You goddamn coward!

01:27:51.019 --> 01:27:53.190
I won't have cowards in my army.

01:28:23.678 --> 01:28:25.180
I had to kick a few butts...

01:28:25.388 --> 01:28:29.600
...but Truscott finally broke through
to those people on the beach.

01:28:29.851 --> 01:28:31.977
Have you seen the casualty lists?

01:28:32.729 --> 01:28:34.271
Yes, I've seen them.

01:28:35.149 --> 01:28:36.857
Whas the word from the coast road?

01:28:37.067 --> 01:28:39.943
The 3rd Division's east of Brolo,
heading toward Messina.

01:28:40.152 --> 01:28:43.612
Les get over there.
I want to go in with the troops.

01:28:43.822 --> 01:28:46.783
You go ahead, George.
I'm not very good at that.

01:28:48.578 --> 01:28:50.121
General Bradley...

01:28:50.331 --> 01:28:53.832
...is time to consider how many
casualties we'd have...

01:28:54.039 --> 01:28:57.419
...if we were still crawling on
that goddamn road.

01:30:24.006 --> 01:30:26.049
Forward, march!

01:30:44.444 --> 01:30:46.403
Don't smirk, Patton.
I shan't kiss you.

01:30:47.572 --> 01:30:52.701
Pity. I shaved close this morning
to prepare for getting smacked by you.

01:31:01.461 --> 01:31:03.378
Forward, march!

01:31:38.246 --> 01:31:40.291
You wanted to see me, George?

01:31:42.918 --> 01:31:44.878
Got a letter here from Ike.

01:31:53.554 --> 01:31:56.765
I was rereading Caesar's
Commentaries last night.

01:31:59.436 --> 01:32:04.231
In battle, Caesar wore a red robe to
distinguish him from his men.

01:32:04.438 --> 01:32:06.985
I was struck by that fact because-

01:32:09.736 --> 01:32:13.447
"Despicable." First time anybody's
ever applied that word to me.

01:32:13.739 --> 01:32:18.037
Well, at least is a personal
reprimand, is not official.

01:32:18.286 --> 01:32:21.789
The man was yellow. He shoulďve
been tried for cowardice and shot.

01:32:22.039 --> 01:32:26.421
People have taken a lot worse
than a little kick in the pants.

01:32:26.670 --> 01:32:30.133
I ruffled his pride a bit.
Whas that compared to war?

01:32:30.799 --> 01:32:34.886
Two weeks ago at Palermo they said
I was the greatest general...

01:32:35.094 --> 01:32:39.476
...since Stonewall Jackson.
- Now they draw cartoons about you.

01:32:39.682 --> 01:32:41.600
Dirty bastard!

01:32:42.061 --> 01:32:46.190
They got me holding a little GI
and kicking him with an iron boot.

01:32:46.398 --> 01:32:48.899
You see that, whas on my boot?
A swastika.

01:32:49.149 --> 01:32:52.445
On my boot.
An iron boot with a swastika!

01:32:56.951 --> 01:33:00.370
"You will apologize to the soldier
you slapped...

01:33:00.997 --> 01:33:05.250
...to all doctors and nurses present
in the tent at the time...

01:33:05.500 --> 01:33:08.546
...to every patient in the tent
who can be reached...

01:33:08.962 --> 01:33:12.341
...and last but not least
to the 7th Army as a whole...

01:33:12.717 --> 01:33:15.594
...through individual units,
one at a time."

01:33:20.765 --> 01:33:22.266
God, I...

01:33:23.977 --> 01:33:25.604
...feel low.

01:33:32.653 --> 01:33:34.154
PATTON:
Oh, God...

01:33:34.403 --> 01:33:36.281
...Thou art my God.

01:33:37.280 --> 01:33:39.367
Early will I seek Thee.

01:33:40.034 --> 01:33:43.120
My soul thirsteth for Thee.

01:33:43.370 --> 01:33:47.833
My flesh longeth for Thee
in a dry and thirsty land.

01:33:48.082 --> 01:33:51.672
So as I have seen Thee
in the sanctuary.

01:33:51.879 --> 01:33:55.093
My soul followeth hard after Thee.

01:33:56.050 --> 01:34:00.095
But those that seek my soul
to destroy it...

01:34:00.304 --> 01:34:03.766
...shall go into the lower parts
of the earth.

01:34:04.434 --> 01:34:07.687
They shall fall by the sword.

01:34:07.896 --> 01:34:11.690
They shall be apportioned for foxes.

01:34:12.776 --> 01:34:15.861
But the king shall rejoice in God.

01:34:16.698 --> 01:34:20.158
Everyone that sweareth by him
shall glory.

01:34:20.909 --> 01:34:25.247
But the mouth of them
that speak lies...

01:34:25.913 --> 01:34:28.208
...shall be stopped.

01:34:32.504 --> 01:34:34.755
Ten-hut!

01:34:36.840 --> 01:34:38.176
PATTON:
At ease.

01:34:50.897 --> 01:34:54.235
I thought I'd stand up here
and let you people see...

01:34:56.109 --> 01:35:00.280
...if I am as big a son of a bitch
as some of you think I am.

01:35:05.119 --> 01:35:07.789
I assure you I had no intention...

01:35:08.662 --> 01:35:12.585
...of being either harsh or cruel
in my treatment of the...

01:35:13.168 --> 01:35:14.838
...soldier in question.

01:35:19.843 --> 01:35:22.428
My sole purpose was to try
to restore in him...

01:35:22.636 --> 01:35:25.724
...some appreciation of his
obligations as a man...

01:35:27.309 --> 01:35:29.059
...and as a soldier.

01:35:30.979 --> 01:35:33.147
If one can shame a coward...

01:35:34.941 --> 01:35:39.277
...I felt one might help him
to regain his self-respect.

01:35:41.824 --> 01:35:43.407
This was on my mind.

01:35:45.743 --> 01:35:48.246
Now, I freely admit...

01:35:48.455 --> 01:35:50.540
...that my method was wrong...

01:35:51.457 --> 01:35:53.709
...but I hope you understand
my motive...

01:35:55.128 --> 01:35:57.214
...and will accept this...

01:35:57.756 --> 01:35:59.507
...explanation...

01:36:01.174 --> 01:36:02.636
...and this...

01:36:04.721 --> 01:36:05.971
...apology.

01:36:08.223 --> 01:36:11.602
- Dismissed.
- Ten-hut!

01:36:17.691 --> 01:36:21.612
Good evening, general. I want to
report on a private poll I'm taking.

01:36:21.821 --> 01:36:22.864
What poll?

01:36:23.071 --> 01:36:24.239
The fan mail.

01:36:24.490 --> 01:36:27.286
Eleven percent con,
89 percent pro.

01:36:27.493 --> 01:36:32.038
And that 11% of protest, in most
cases, is both obscene and anonymous.

01:36:32.288 --> 01:36:36.002
But the pro letters are mostly from
relatives and servicemen.

01:36:36.210 --> 01:36:39.755
"I want you to know we're proud
our son is serving in your army.

01:36:40.004 --> 01:36:43.676
From the newspaper, we're not clear
exactly what you did and why...

01:36:44.136 --> 01:36:46.595
...but we want you to know
we're for you.

01:36:46.804 --> 01:36:48.639
Keep going, and God bless you."

01:36:49.307 --> 01:36:51.059
Keep going, huh?

01:36:51.267 --> 01:36:52.686
Where?

01:36:56.440 --> 01:37:00.733
I thought you might like a sip
of wine, general. Is New Year's.

01:37:00.944 --> 01:37:03.113
You didn't celebrate at all
last night.

01:37:10.868 --> 01:37:13.332
I'm sick of sitting around this...

01:37:13.582 --> 01:37:15.791
...royal doghouse.

01:37:15.999 --> 01:37:18.961
We've taken Sicily.
I'm ready for a new assignment.

01:37:19.628 --> 01:37:24.383
Maybe you've got it.
Here's a radio message, just came in.

01:37:28.887 --> 01:37:30.014
Cod.

01:37:31.223 --> 01:37:32.641
I've been relieved.

01:37:35.018 --> 01:37:37.939
They've relieved me from command
of the 7th Army.

01:37:38.773 --> 01:37:40.650
I don't believe it.

01:37:43.610 --> 01:37:44.653
Happy New Year.

01:37:51.077 --> 01:37:52.744
Just a minute, sir.

01:37:53.620 --> 01:37:56.332
Since they're sure to give you
another command...

01:37:56.539 --> 01:38:00.043
...isn't it logical they'd
relieve you here first?

01:38:01.211 --> 01:38:04.463
You mean command of all American
troops going into Europe?

01:38:04.673 --> 01:38:08.260
Is possible. I know is been
discussed from time to time.

01:38:08.511 --> 01:38:12.974
The logic of it is so obvious,
it couldn't mean anything else.

01:38:14.475 --> 01:38:19.021
Sir, I'm going to open
this bottle of wine.

01:38:19.437 --> 01:38:20.815
No, Sir Cod...

01:38:21.066 --> 01:38:24.651
...but if you find a bottle of cognac,
I'll help you drink it.

01:38:31.867 --> 01:38:35.745
- How you feeling tonight, general?
- Not bad, not bad at all.

01:38:35.955 --> 01:38:39.043
- Get me some writing paper, will you?
- Yes, sir.

01:38:39.791 --> 01:38:42.587
Your wife ever give you the devil
for not writing?

01:38:42.795 --> 01:38:44.213
All the time, sir.

01:38:44.422 --> 01:38:48.426
Only I don't write as often as you
do. Don't seem to get around to it.

01:38:49.300 --> 01:38:50.804
Lucky for us we got them.

01:38:51.804 --> 01:38:55.223
Who wants to marry a couple of
broken-down old horse captains?

01:38:55.431 --> 01:38:58.228
Thas what my wife says to me
every time I come home, sir.

01:38:59.395 --> 01:39:01.064
Why are you up so late, George?

01:39:01.271 --> 01:39:03.984
Thought you'd like a nice hot bath
or something.

01:39:12.032 --> 01:39:15.535
I got this sleeping pill from the doc,
just in case you need it.

01:39:16.827 --> 01:39:18.455
Sleeping pill!

01:39:18.996 --> 01:39:22.043
- Whas going on here?
- I heard the news, sir.

01:39:22.251 --> 01:39:25.546
- They announced it on the radio.
- What news?

01:39:26.421 --> 01:39:30.968
About General Bradley, sir. How they
gave him the top American command.

01:39:32.802 --> 01:39:34.096
Oh.

01:39:35.305 --> 01:39:36.598
Oh, yeah.

01:39:38.975 --> 01:39:42.227
I just thought you might be
feeling kind of low, sir.

01:39:59.204 --> 01:40:02.249
Your writing things, sir.
Here on the desk, sir.

01:40:02.876 --> 01:40:05.543
Yeah. Thank you, George.

01:40:07.962 --> 01:40:09.340
One little dog face.

01:40:09.591 --> 01:40:13.010
One measly little slap.
Thas what done it.

01:40:15.639 --> 01:40:17.682
Ah, George.

01:40:19.599 --> 01:40:22.477
I wish I'd kissed the son of a bitch.

01:43:51.241 --> 01:43:55.620
He's paying tribute to the Free French
Forces under DeGaulle and Leclerc.

01:44:11.891 --> 01:44:13.933
And to the people of the Resistance...

01:44:14.141 --> 01:44:17.145
...who risk their lives
to help destroy the Germans.

01:44:24.405 --> 01:44:27.117
"France will be free again.
I give you my word."

01:44:54.397 --> 01:44:58.525
"Just as Free French troops liberated
Corsica, Napoleon's place of birth...

01:44:58.777 --> 01:45:03.114
...I will someday land in France to
liberate the birthplace of Lafayette."

01:45:07.119 --> 01:45:10.415
General, the reporters would like
a word with you.

01:45:13.334 --> 01:45:15.255
- Good afternoon.
- General.

01:45:15.462 --> 01:45:18.505
Can you tell us the purpose
of this visit to Corsica?

01:45:18.716 --> 01:45:20.552
General Eisenhower ordered me here.

01:45:20.761 --> 01:45:25.139
You wrote the mother of the boy you
slapped, "The rat shoulďve been shot."

01:45:25.390 --> 01:45:27.726
- Is that true, general?
- No comment.

01:45:27.933 --> 01:45:30.438
Sir, I understand
Gen. Alexander suggested...

01:45:30.688 --> 01:45:33.609
...you take over Gen. Clark's
Italian campaign...

01:45:33.859 --> 01:45:36.111
...but it was killed
due to the incident.

01:45:36.362 --> 01:45:39.404
- No comment.
- Can you say where you're going, sir?

01:45:39.614 --> 01:45:42.451
Off the record,
Eisenhower's ordered me to Malta.

01:45:42.659 --> 01:45:43.788
Interview concluded.

01:45:43.995 --> 01:45:46.746
You plan on slapping
any soldiers there, general?

01:46:17.115 --> 01:46:20.536
PATTON: In 1528, these forts
were defended by...

01:46:20.788 --> 01:46:25.625
...400 Knights of Malta
and 800 mercenaries...

01:46:25.875 --> 01:46:30.298
...against a force of 40,000 Turks.

01:46:31.090 --> 01:46:32.383
Codman.

01:46:35.177 --> 01:46:38.225
- Still no word from Gen. Eisenhower?
- No, sir.

01:46:38.723 --> 01:46:42.394
Not even a response about
the two turkeys I sent for Christmas?

01:46:42.644 --> 01:46:44.061
No, sir.

01:46:44.940 --> 01:46:48.444
Go ahead, gentlemen.
Take a closer look for yourselves.

01:46:51.822 --> 01:46:56.161
Looks like you boys have hitched
your wagon to a falling star.

01:46:57.204 --> 01:47:00.248
Pass the word.
If anyone wants out, I'll understand.

01:47:00.456 --> 01:47:04.086
Sir, I can speak for the entire staff.

01:47:04.670 --> 01:47:08.883
We want to stay with you, no matter
what duty you're assigned to.

01:47:12.512 --> 01:47:15.766
Up in London, they're planning
the invasion of Europe.

01:47:17.852 --> 01:47:20.562
I've trained my mind,
body and spirit for that.

01:47:20.813 --> 01:47:23.276
What, in Goďs name, am I doing here?

01:47:25.652 --> 01:47:27.029
All right.

01:47:27.319 --> 01:47:29.323
Les get on to Cairo.

01:47:29.989 --> 01:47:32.452
See if the pyramids
are still standing.

01:48:54.086 --> 01:48:57.339
- This place is for me?
- Yes, sir. This way, sir.

01:48:58.632 --> 01:49:01.719
Whoever found it has a genius
for cloak and dagger.

01:49:19.740 --> 01:49:21.368
Who picked this cathouse?

01:49:21.619 --> 01:49:23.495
I think it was Gen. Smith, sir.

01:49:23.704 --> 01:49:25.706
To spite me, that son of a bitch.

01:49:25.916 --> 01:49:29.712
- Welcome to London, Georgie.
- Bedell. How are you?

01:49:29.918 --> 01:49:32.172
- Is Ike here?
- He asked me to brief you.

01:49:32.383 --> 01:49:34.258
Would you excuse us, please?

01:49:36.594 --> 01:49:38.638
Let me put you straight about Ike.

01:49:38.888 --> 01:49:42.184
We hear a lot about you
criticizing his decisions.

01:49:42.433 --> 01:49:45.478
Not really. You know me.
I'm just an old fool.

01:49:45.686 --> 01:49:48.816
At times, I do wonder whether
he isn't a limey at heart.

01:49:49.024 --> 01:49:52.820
George, this is the toughest coalition
ever attempted in history.

01:49:53.070 --> 01:49:57.200
Ike's trying to hold it together
and lick the Germans at the same time.

01:49:57.450 --> 01:49:59.494
- Is a hell of a job.
- I understand.

01:50:00.118 --> 01:50:04.083
You have an important assignment
connected to the Normandy invasion.

01:50:04.292 --> 01:50:08.547
Good. I've studied the Overlord Plan
and there's a number of flaws in it.

01:50:08.755 --> 01:50:13.509
You can't depend on Monty taking
Cannes by D-day. He'll never make it.

01:50:13.760 --> 01:50:16.847
I've drawn up an alternate plan
to land at Calais...

01:50:17.098 --> 01:50:21.395
...following an air bombardment-
- Will you just listen for a change?

01:50:21.645 --> 01:50:24.354
Ike stood by you when everyone,
I mean everyone...

01:50:24.605 --> 01:50:27.235
...wanted Patton
with a rope around his neck.

01:50:32.823 --> 01:50:36.619
We're gonna let it leak out
that you are here undercover.

01:50:36.828 --> 01:50:39.958
That you're preparing to invade
at the Pas de Calais.

01:50:40.165 --> 01:50:42.793
We hope to pin down
the German 15th Army there...

01:50:43.044 --> 01:50:45.881
...so that they can't be used
against us at Normandy.

01:50:46.255 --> 01:50:48.049
Is that all I'm good for?

01:50:48.259 --> 01:50:52.472
We're going to build an army
of 12 divisions around you.

01:50:52.722 --> 01:50:54.766
All fictitious, of course.

01:50:54.974 --> 01:50:57.896
Dummy troop concentrations,
dummy landing craft...

01:50:58.104 --> 01:51:00.396
...simulated radio traffic.

01:51:00.604 --> 01:51:05.236
The Germans are convinced that you
will lead the main invasion effort.

01:51:05.654 --> 01:51:07.574
Their agents will spot you soon...

01:51:07.781 --> 01:51:10.410
...then we can move you to Knutsford.

01:51:10.617 --> 01:51:13.913
- What do I do there?
- Nothing. Absolutely nothing.

01:51:15.081 --> 01:51:18.124
Frankly, George, you're on probation.

01:51:18.334 --> 01:51:20.420
Take my advice and behave yourself.

01:51:20.630 --> 01:51:22.089
Remember...

01:51:22.381 --> 01:51:25.424
...your worst enemy
is your own big mouth.

01:52:20.782 --> 01:52:24.284
Look at this nasty-faced
son of a bitch. Ready for combat.

01:52:24.495 --> 01:52:27.162
I'll call him William
as in "the Conqueror."

01:52:27.539 --> 01:52:31.460
- Sir, should we leave him in the car?
- No. Good afternoon, ladies.

01:52:31.710 --> 01:52:33.419
Good afternoon.

01:52:38.259 --> 01:52:39.885
Watch this, Cod.

01:52:40.177 --> 01:52:42.639
- Sir, he'll kill that dog.
- I'll hold him.

01:52:52.066 --> 01:52:55.946
I'm terribly sorry, general.
Did Abigail frighten your dog?

01:52:57.363 --> 01:52:59.282
Thas quite all right, madam.

01:53:00.159 --> 01:53:01.577
This way, sir.

01:53:03.829 --> 01:53:05.332
Your name isn't William.

01:53:06.332 --> 01:53:07.833
Is Willie.

01:53:10.838 --> 01:53:12.338
WOMAN:
My dear friends.

01:53:12.673 --> 01:53:16.927
General George S. Patton, Jr.,
has accepted our invitation...

01:53:17.178 --> 01:53:18.722
...to say a few words to you...

01:53:18.971 --> 01:53:21.726
...on the occasion
of this inaugural ceremony.

01:53:27.441 --> 01:53:31.110
General Patton is not here
in an official capacity...

01:53:31.487 --> 01:53:33.947
...and I have assured him
most earnestly...

01:53:34.197 --> 01:53:36.618
...that nothing he says
will be quoted.

01:53:39.997 --> 01:53:43.081
May I present General Patton.

01:53:54.347 --> 01:53:56.765
- Remember, sir, watch your language.
- Yeah.

01:53:57.265 --> 01:53:58.933
My dear ladies.

01:53:59.603 --> 01:54:01.437
Until today...

01:54:01.688 --> 01:54:06.818
...my only experience
at welcoming has been...

01:54:07.069 --> 01:54:12.198
...to welcome Germans and Italians
to the infernal region.

01:54:13.701 --> 01:54:16.288
At this I have been
quite successful...

01:54:16.497 --> 01:54:19.667
...since the troops, which I have had
the honor to command...

01:54:19.875 --> 01:54:22.503
...have, to date, killed or captured...

01:54:22.754 --> 01:54:26.340
...some 170,000 of our enemies.

01:54:35.101 --> 01:54:40.232
I feel that such clubs as these
are of very real value...

01:54:40.605 --> 01:54:43.444
...because I believe
with Mr. Bernard Shaw...

01:54:43.653 --> 01:54:47.365
...that the British and the Americans
are two peoples...

01:54:47.617 --> 01:54:51.284
...separated by a common language.

01:54:53.955 --> 01:54:59.002
Since it is the destiny of the British
and Americans to rule the world...

01:55:00.547 --> 01:55:02.549
...the better we know each other...

01:55:02.800 --> 01:55:04.633
...the better we will do it.

01:55:05.886 --> 01:55:08.390
The Russians,
don't forget the Russians.

01:55:08.806 --> 01:55:10.516
I think that a club like this...

01:55:10.766 --> 01:55:14.229
...is an ideal place
for promoting mutual understanding.

01:55:15.061 --> 01:55:20.487
Because as soon as our soldiers meet
and get to know the English ladies...

01:55:20.944 --> 01:55:26.325
...and write home and tell our women
just how lovely you truly are...

01:55:30.996 --> 01:55:33.960
...then the sooner the American ladies
will get jealous...

01:55:34.209 --> 01:55:37.129
...and force this war
to a quick termination.

01:55:41.219 --> 01:55:46.139
And then I'll get the chance to go
to the Pacific and kill Japanese.

01:56:04.787 --> 01:56:06.204
NARRATOR:
All over the nation...

01:56:06.454 --> 01:56:10.418
...mass meetings are held to protest
General Patton 's statement...

01:56:10.668 --> 01:56:13.461
...that Britain and America
will rule the post war world.

01:56:13.713 --> 01:56:15.633
That Russia will have no say.

01:56:15.840 --> 01:56:20.138
Congressional leaders like Senator
Clayburn Foss are quick to react.

01:56:20.388 --> 01:56:23.097
This man has insulted
our Russian allies...

01:56:23.348 --> 01:56:26.228
...implying Anglo-American world rule.

01:56:26.477 --> 01:56:29.564
In my opinion, he should be
severely disciplined.

01:56:29.897 --> 01:56:31.859
This time I didn't do a damn thing.

01:56:32.110 --> 01:56:34.780
They promised there
wouldn't be any reporters.

01:56:35.029 --> 01:56:37.281
I made a few remarks off the record.

01:56:37.489 --> 01:56:39.952
Ike told you to keep your mouth shut.

01:56:40.202 --> 01:56:43.997
You know how suspicious the Russians
are of the British and us.

01:56:44.205 --> 01:56:47.503
I was only trying to be polite
to the old ladies.

01:56:47.751 --> 01:56:53.175
If I'd seen the Russians there, I'd
have mentioned the sons of bitches.

01:56:53.508 --> 01:56:56.470
Bedell, I don't know
anything about politics.

01:56:56.720 --> 01:56:58.638
I have no political ambitions.

01:56:58.889 --> 01:57:01.892
All I want to do is
to command an army in combat.

01:57:02.143 --> 01:57:04.188
Well, is out of our hands now.

01:57:04.438 --> 01:57:07.733
Ike sent a message last night
to the chief of staff.

01:57:07.983 --> 01:57:13.156
Now is up to General Marshall
whether you stay here as a decoy...

01:57:13.405 --> 01:57:15.408
...or he sends you home.

01:57:17.911 --> 01:57:19.581
