02:10:33.026 --> 02:10:34.488
Now come on! Hold it!

02:10:34.736 --> 02:10:37.992
Hey, dummy, hold the fricking tank!

02:10:43.247 --> 02:10:44.706
Thas it. Come on.

02:10:44.957 --> 02:10:46.334
Good boy.

02:10:49.129 --> 02:10:50.754
- Hold it up there.
- General!

02:10:51.006 --> 02:10:53.340
General Bradley wants to have
a word with you.

02:10:53.593 --> 02:10:56.471
Okay. Come on!

02:10:57.637 --> 02:11:01.976
Okay. Hold it up. Take over.

02:11:09.526 --> 02:11:12.197
George, you'd make a good traffic cop.

02:11:13.948 --> 02:11:16.577
George this drive has been
magnificent...

02:11:16.826 --> 02:11:19.705
...but I'm sorry to say
I have to slow you down.

02:11:19.915 --> 02:11:24.084
- What the hell for?
- We'll have to cut off your supplies.

02:11:24.333 --> 02:11:28.132
Gasoline, ammunition, everything.
We're up against new priorities.

02:11:28.380 --> 02:11:32.011
- I think I smell Montgomery.
- Take it easy, George.

02:11:32.260 --> 02:11:35.264
There are serious issues involved.
Political issues.

02:11:35.516 --> 02:11:37.351
By God, it is Montgomery.

02:11:37.600 --> 02:11:41.521
The launching sites for the B-2 bombs
are all in his area.

02:11:41.772 --> 02:11:43.816
Churchill wants those bases destroyed.

02:11:44.275 --> 02:11:47.446
Hitler kills more civilians
in London than soldiers.

02:11:47.652 --> 02:11:49.365
Expect Montgomery to do anything?

02:11:50.115 --> 02:11:53.827
You give me gasoline and I'll gain
ground with it, kill Germans too.

02:11:54.079 --> 02:11:55.997
Give me 400,000 gallons.
I'll go to Berlin.

02:11:56.289 --> 02:11:57.876
George, I can't do it.

02:11:58.124 --> 02:12:00.044
The Siegfried line
is an empty shell.

02:12:00.293 --> 02:12:02.462
They stripped the equipment
and sent it east.

02:12:02.711 --> 02:12:05.507
Is crawling with cows.
I can punch through in two days.

02:12:05.759 --> 02:12:08.761
There's no use in arguing with me.
It wasn't my idea.

02:12:08.968 --> 02:12:11.015
Why did you pick me to command?

02:12:11.264 --> 02:12:13.305
I didn't pick you.

02:12:15.143 --> 02:12:16.645
Ike picked you.

02:12:20.025 --> 02:12:22.487
George, you have performed
brilliantly.

02:12:22.861 --> 02:12:24.612
You are loyal, dedicated.

02:12:24.863 --> 02:12:27.699
You're one of the best I've got,
but you don't know when to shut up.

02:12:27.949 --> 02:12:31.663
George, you're a pain in the neck.

02:12:35.376 --> 02:12:37.628
I have a lot of faults, Brad.

02:12:37.877 --> 02:12:40.339
But ingratitude isn't one of them.

02:12:40.590 --> 02:12:42.091
I owe you a lot.

02:12:43.260 --> 02:12:46.889
Hell, I know I'm a prima donna.
I admit it.

02:12:47.179 --> 02:12:50.432
What I can't stand about Monty is,
he won't admit it.

02:13:15.838 --> 02:13:19.049
Captain, the Bailey's run out of gas.

02:13:19.509 --> 02:13:21.303
The point tank has run out too.

02:13:22.972 --> 02:13:25.265
And there's a kraut column up ahead.

02:13:25.681 --> 02:13:27.142
Yeah, I know.

02:15:29.323 --> 02:15:31.244
PATTON:
Were you in command here, captain?

02:15:32.744 --> 02:15:33.829
I was in command.

02:15:34.830 --> 02:15:38.666
My tank platoon was supporting
an infantry company.

02:15:38.919 --> 02:15:43.756
Tanks ran out of gas,
so we had to fight it out.

02:15:45.259 --> 02:15:47.929
We started 11:00 last night.

02:15:49.347 --> 02:15:51.474
Finished a couple hours ago.

02:15:53.643 --> 02:15:58.148
This morning the fighting
was hand-to-hand.

02:16:46.536 --> 02:16:48.413
I had a dream last night.

02:16:50.624 --> 02:16:53.835
In my dream it came to me...

02:16:54.047 --> 02:16:57.382
...that right now the whole Nazi Reich
is mine for the taking.

02:16:57.592 --> 02:17:01.972
Think about that, Cod.
I was nearly sent home in disgrace.

02:17:02.680 --> 02:17:05.308
Now I have precisely
the right instrument...

02:17:05.516 --> 02:17:10.314
...at precisely the right moment of
history and exactly the right place.

02:17:10.607 --> 02:17:11.941
The Saar?

02:17:12.148 --> 02:17:14.277
This will change too, very quickly.

02:17:14.485 --> 02:17:17.111
Like a planet spinning off
into the universe.

02:17:17.364 --> 02:17:20.199
A moment like this won't come again
for 1000 years.

02:17:20.407 --> 02:17:23.243
All I need is a few
miserable gallons of gasoline.

02:17:23.621 --> 02:17:27.207
Right now, the weak spot is here.

02:17:28.751 --> 02:17:32.214
In 10 days, we could be in Berlin.

02:17:32.464 --> 02:17:35.966
What about the fortifications
that were done in Metz?

02:17:37.804 --> 02:17:39.973
Fixed fortifications, huh?

02:17:40.223 --> 02:17:43.267
Monuments to the stupidity of man.

02:17:44.061 --> 02:17:47.564
When mountain ranges and oceans
could be overcome...

02:17:47.815 --> 02:17:49.773
...anything built by man
can be overcome.

02:17:54.573 --> 02:17:57.243
You know how I'm sure
they're finished out there?

02:17:59.410 --> 02:18:00.788
The carts.

02:18:02.540 --> 02:18:05.791
They're using carts to move
their wounded and the supplies.

02:18:07.670 --> 02:18:11.635
The carts came to me in my dream.
I couldn't figure it out.

02:18:12.968 --> 02:18:14.763
Then I remembered...

02:18:16.596 --> 02:18:21.019
...that nightmare in the snow.
The agonizing retreat from Moscow.

02:18:21.894 --> 02:18:23.731
How cold it was.

02:18:27.151 --> 02:18:30.820
They threw the wounded and what was
left of the supplies in the carts.

02:18:32.074 --> 02:18:33.951
Napoleon was finished.

02:18:36.204 --> 02:18:38.956
Not any color left.
Not even the red of blood.

02:18:40.208 --> 02:18:41.877
Only the snow.

02:18:46.922 --> 02:18:48.342
Look at this, Cod.

02:18:56.059 --> 02:18:57.519
I love it.

02:19:01.522 --> 02:19:03.776
God help me, I do love it so.

02:19:07.906 --> 02:19:09.448
I love it more than my life.

02:19:18.669 --> 02:19:21.921
NARRATOR: Paris is liberated,
and French troops lead the way.

02:19:22.715 --> 02:19:27.429
The Allies march into the city
after four years of Nazi occupation.

02:19:27.846 --> 02:19:30.682
The hard-fighting French
2nd Armored Division...

02:19:30.891 --> 02:19:33.269
...under Major General
Jacques Leclerc...

02:19:33.477 --> 02:19:35.312
...gets an unforgettable welcome...

02:19:35.771 --> 02:19:37.857
...as they enter their beloved Paris.

02:19:42.948 --> 02:19:44.864
In a powerful drive to the north...

02:19:45.074 --> 02:19:48.661
...General Montgomery cuts off and
bypasses the French coastal towns...

02:19:48.911 --> 02:19:51.332
...of Boulogne, Calais and Dunkirk.

02:19:51.579 --> 02:19:54.835
Pushing on to capture the vital
Belgian port of Antwerp.

02:20:00.840 --> 02:20:02.592
Meanwhile, the main body
of Patton 's army...

02:20:02.802 --> 02:20:07.139
...resupplied now and rolling like a
juggernaut, slashes toward the Saar.

02:20:08.100 --> 02:20:10.145
Nazi resistance appears to crumble.

02:20:10.394 --> 02:20:15.108
It seems that nothing can stop our
troops from driving on into Germany.

02:20:23.867 --> 02:20:26.997
- Sir, General Bradley on your line.
- Good, good.

02:20:33.129 --> 02:20:35.881
Brad, listen, I've got a bridgehead
across the Saar.

02:20:36.132 --> 02:20:37.301
I'm on my way to Germany.

02:20:37.592 --> 02:20:40.176
Wait a minute, George.
There's a lot of trouble up north.

02:20:40.428 --> 02:20:45.559
I want you to transfer tank armor
to Middleton's 8th Corps right away.

02:20:45.976 --> 02:20:47.521
Brad, you can't do that.

02:20:47.895 --> 02:20:50.857
George, listen.
I don't have time to argue.

02:20:51.107 --> 02:20:53.902
There's a lot of enemy activity
up around Ardennes.

02:20:54.194 --> 02:20:56.446
No, I don't know how serious it is...

02:20:56.696 --> 02:21:01.202
...but Ike wants us to meet
with Bedell Smith tomorrow at Verdun.

02:21:01.452 --> 02:21:02.662
Be there at 1100.

02:21:03.163 --> 02:21:04.538
Yes, sir.

02:21:45.504 --> 02:21:48.338
PATTON: There's absolutely no reason
for us to assume...

02:21:48.548 --> 02:21:51.261
...that the Germans are mounting
a major offense.

02:21:52.553 --> 02:21:56.683
The weather is awful
and their supplies are low.

02:21:57.600 --> 02:22:01.313
The Germans haven't mounted a winter
attack since Frederick the Great.

02:22:04.023 --> 02:22:07.195
Therefore I believe thas exactly
what they're going to do.

02:22:49.034 --> 02:22:51.953
I want you to start making
contingency plans...

02:22:52.204 --> 02:22:53.915
...for pulling out
of our eastward attack.

02:22:54.290 --> 02:22:57.084
Changing directions 90 degrees,
moving up to Luxembourg.

02:22:58.876 --> 02:23:00.714
Don't look so stunned, gentlemen.

02:23:01.423 --> 02:23:04.050
I want you to plan
for three possible axes of attack.

02:23:04.260 --> 02:23:06.178
From Diekirch, due north.

02:23:06.430 --> 02:23:10.726
From Orléans to Bastogne.

02:23:10.934 --> 02:23:14.478
From Neufchâteau against the German
left flank.

02:23:34.793 --> 02:23:37.131
We've identified four German armies:

02:23:37.379 --> 02:23:42.385
The 7th, the 5th Panzer,
6th SS Panzer and the 15th.

02:23:42.930 --> 02:23:44.931
They've hit us with 26 divisions.

02:23:45.181 --> 02:23:48.060
They've overran two regimens
of the 106th Division.

02:23:48.308 --> 02:23:51.395
And 7500 of our men
were forced to surrender.

02:23:51.772 --> 02:23:54.318
Our concern is that von Rundstedt...

02:23:54.525 --> 02:23:58.488
...has the 101 st Airborne trapped
here at Bastogne.

02:24:01.408 --> 02:24:05.579
Bastogne, by the way, is the key
to this entire area.

02:24:06.372 --> 02:24:10.168
If we can hold it, we can break up
the entire German offensive.

02:24:10.794 --> 02:24:13.505
If they take it,
we're in serious trouble.

02:24:14.631 --> 02:24:17.009
Ike wants to know if anybody can go...

02:24:17.218 --> 02:24:20.472
...and relieve the 101 st
before they're torn to pieces.

02:24:22.723 --> 02:24:25.060
There's nothing Montgomery can do.

02:24:25.309 --> 02:24:27.688
At any rate, not for some weeks.

02:24:28.395 --> 02:24:30.399
What about you, George?

02:24:31.318 --> 02:24:33.735
I can attack with three divisions
in 48 hours.

02:24:37.738 --> 02:24:39.368
I'd give myself some leeway.

02:24:39.951 --> 02:24:42.078
Ike wants a realistic estimate,
George.

02:24:42.330 --> 02:24:46.460
You're in the middle of a fight now.
Is over a hundred miles to Bastogne.

02:24:46.710 --> 02:24:49.046
My staff's already working
out the details.

02:24:51.338 --> 02:24:54.385
Frankly, I don't see how
is possible.

02:24:54.846 --> 02:24:56.888
Not in this kind of weather.

02:24:57.515 --> 02:25:00.348
I should have thought you'd want
to fall back and regroup.

02:25:00.600 --> 02:25:03.354
Not me. I don't like to pay
for the same real estate twice.

02:25:03.604 --> 02:25:04.939
TEDDER:
But what about your men?

02:25:05.274 --> 02:25:09.569
You can't cart them off 100 miles,
expecting them to attack without rest.

02:25:09.987 --> 02:25:11.112
I trained these men.

02:25:11.364 --> 02:25:13.281
They'll do what I tell them to do.

02:25:13.532 --> 02:25:17.245
We hadn't realized you were
so popular with your troops, general.

02:25:18.577 --> 02:25:22.542
I'm not. They'll do it
because they're good soldiers.

02:25:22.791 --> 02:25:26.673
And because they realize, as I do,
that we can still lose this war.

02:25:29.926 --> 02:25:32.678
Then I think I can speak
for Field Marshal Montgomery.

02:25:33.552 --> 02:25:36.017
He'd say you're asking
the impossible of your men.

02:25:36.266 --> 02:25:37.809
Of course he would.

02:25:38.060 --> 02:25:41.314
Cause he's never realized thas
what we're in business for.

02:26:59.567 --> 02:27:02.032
General McAuliffe refused
a German surrender demand.

02:27:02.281 --> 02:27:03.908
You know what he said?

02:27:05.034 --> 02:27:06.287
What?

02:27:06.661 --> 02:27:08.288
He said, "Nuts."

02:27:10.497 --> 02:27:11.750
Keep them moving, colonel.

02:27:12.001 --> 02:27:14.336
A man that eloquent has to be saved.

02:29:32.577 --> 02:29:34.494
This is where it pays off.

02:29:34.872 --> 02:29:36.499
The training and discipline.

02:29:37.583 --> 02:29:39.709
No other outfit in the world.

02:29:40.420 --> 02:29:44.091
Pulled out of a winter battle,
move a hundred miles.

02:29:44.382 --> 02:29:48.471
Going to a major attack with no rest,
no sleep, no hot food.

02:29:48.680 --> 02:29:52.350
God! God, I'm proud of these men!

02:30:18.005 --> 02:30:22.135
Sir, von Rundsteds thrown another
panzer division against Bastogne.

02:30:22.383 --> 02:30:24.595
101 st Airborne's barely holding on.

02:30:24.804 --> 02:30:29.183
We need damned air cover. If we had
decent weather, we might make it.

02:30:29.643 --> 02:30:31.688
CARVER:
General Mason, sir.

02:30:46.288 --> 02:30:49.415
Hello, Mase?
Listen, we're short on foot soldiers.

02:30:49.665 --> 02:30:53.377
Cannibalize your antiaircraft units
and turn them into riflemen.

02:30:53.587 --> 02:30:55.464
Yes, every last one you can find.

02:30:55.716 --> 02:30:57.006
Good evening, general.

02:30:57.257 --> 02:31:00.469
I just got the weather report
for tomorrow. More snow.

02:31:00.720 --> 02:31:02.681
There goes our air cover.

02:31:02.932 --> 02:31:05.601
We may have to wait
for better weather.

02:31:05.847 --> 02:31:10.732
Brave men dying up there. I won't
wait, not an hour, not a minute.

02:31:13.065 --> 02:31:14.485
Going to keep moving.

02:31:14.735 --> 02:31:16.529
Is that clear?

02:31:18.616 --> 02:31:22.162
We're going to attack all night
and attack tomorrow morning!

02:31:23.204 --> 02:31:25.497
If we're not victorious...

02:31:27.793 --> 02:31:29.793
...let no one come back alive.

02:31:41.557 --> 02:31:43.268
You know something, general?

02:31:43.519 --> 02:31:47.816
Sometimes, they can't tell when
you're acting and when you're not.

02:31:49.566 --> 02:31:51.777
It isn't important for them to know.

02:31:53.320 --> 02:31:55.532
Is only important for me to know.

02:32:02.582 --> 02:32:05.962
- You want to see me, general?
- Oh, yeah, chaplain.

02:32:06.168 --> 02:32:08.796
I'm tired of 3rd Army
having to fight Germans...

02:32:09.047 --> 02:32:11.383
...with supreme command,
no gasoline...

02:32:11.593 --> 02:32:13.592
...and now this ungodly weather.

02:32:13.845 --> 02:32:15.931
I want a prayer, a weather prayer.

02:32:16.975 --> 02:32:18.308
A weather prayer, sir?

02:32:18.559 --> 02:32:21.603
Yes, les see if you can't get God
working with us.

02:32:21.854 --> 02:32:24.316
Gonna take a thick rug
for that kind of praying.

02:32:24.565 --> 02:32:26.820
I don't care if it
takes a flying carpet.

02:32:27.026 --> 02:32:29.946
I don't know how this
will be received, general.

02:32:30.196 --> 02:32:33.118
Praying for good weather
so we can kill our fellow man.

02:32:33.366 --> 02:32:36.495
I assure you, because of
my relations with the Almighty...

02:32:36.745 --> 02:32:39.958
...if you write a good prayer,
we'll have good weather.

02:32:40.249 --> 02:32:42.878
And I expect that prayer
within an hour.

02:32:43.671 --> 02:32:44.963
Yes, sir.

02:33:15.623 --> 02:33:18.544
"Almighty and most merciful Father...

02:33:19.462 --> 02:33:21.922
...we humbly beseech Thee...

02:33:22.173 --> 02:33:24.382
...of Thy great goodness...

02:33:25.303 --> 02:33:28.762
...to restrain this
immoderate weather...

02:33:30.016 --> 02:33:32.309
...with which we've had to contend.

02:33:34.478 --> 02:33:37.316
Grant us fair weather for battle.

02:33:38.441 --> 02:33:40.233
Graciously hearken to us...

02:33:41.362 --> 02:33:43.573
...as soldiers who call upon Thee...

02:33:44.073 --> 02:33:46.534
...that armed with Thy power...

02:33:46.908 --> 02:33:49.872
...we may advance
from victory to victory...

02:33:50.079 --> 02:33:52.458
...and crush the oppression...

02:33:52.707 --> 02:33:55.253
...and wickedness of our enemies...

02:33:55.460 --> 02:33:57.754
...and establish Thy justice...

02:33:58.589 --> 02:34:01.925
...among men and nations.

02:34:05.305 --> 02:34:06.557
Amen."

02:34:21.990 --> 02:34:23.451
Weather's perfect.

02:34:24.744 --> 02:34:27.581
Cod, get me that chaplain.

02:34:27.832 --> 02:34:30.835
He's in good with the Lord
and I want to decorate him.

02:34:58.449 --> 02:35:00.826
Hiya, general!

02:35:38.704 --> 02:35:41.331
NARRATOR: Supported by medium bombers
and fighter bombers...

02:35:41.582 --> 02:35:44.126
...flying sorties
against German positions...

02:35:44.377 --> 02:35:46.004
...elements of the 3rd Army...

02:35:46.211 --> 02:35:48.797
...spearheaded by the
4th Armored Division...

02:35:49.049 --> 02:35:50.591
...drive into Bastogne...

02:35:50.800 --> 02:35:53.304
...to relieve its 18,000 defenders...

02:35:53.511 --> 02:35:55.181
...on the day after Christmas.

02:35:56.308 --> 02:35:59.603
During this operation,
3rd Army moved farther and faster...

02:35:59.852 --> 02:36:02.271
...and engaged more divisions
in less time...

02:36:02.522 --> 02:36:06.235
...than any other army in the history
of the United States.

02:39:21.958 --> 02:39:23.585
Excuse me, sir.

02:39:23.835 --> 02:39:26.587
General Katkov would like to know
if you'll join him...

02:39:26.839 --> 02:39:29.591
...to drink to the surrender
of Germany.

02:39:29.883 --> 02:39:32.220
My compliments to the general.

02:39:32.470 --> 02:39:35.640
Please inform him that I do not care
to drink with him...

02:39:35.848 --> 02:39:38.560
...or any other Russian
son of a bitch.

02:39:39.061 --> 02:39:41.272
Sir...

02:39:41.482 --> 02:39:43.315
...I cannot tell the general that.

02:39:44.776 --> 02:39:46.277
You tell him that.

02:39:46.570 --> 02:39:48.154
Tell him word for word.

02:40:10.430 --> 02:40:13.183
The general says he thinks that...

02:40:13.432 --> 02:40:15.310
...you are a son of a bitch too.

02:40:20.899 --> 02:40:23.946
Okay. I'll drink to that.

02:40:24.197 --> 02:40:25.946
One son of a bitch to another.

02:41:08.496 --> 02:41:10.875
Is it true that Roosevelt,
before he died...

02:41:11.125 --> 02:41:13.295
...promised you
a command in the Pacific?

02:41:13.545 --> 02:41:18.298
Yes. But now that he's gone, I don't
think there's much chance of that.

02:41:18.550 --> 02:41:20.762
Doug MacArthur
doesn't want me up there.

02:41:20.968 --> 02:41:24.138
We're told of "wonder weapons"
the Germans were working on:

02:41:24.388 --> 02:41:26.851
Long-range rockets,
push-button bombing...

02:41:27.102 --> 02:41:29.519
...weapons that don't need soldiers.

02:41:29.812 --> 02:41:31.190
"Wonder weapon"?

02:41:32.108 --> 02:41:34.568
My God, I don't see
the wonder in them.

02:41:35.152 --> 02:41:39.323
Killing without heroics. Nothing
is glorified, nothing is reaffirmed.

02:41:39.947 --> 02:41:43.496
No heroes, no cowards, no troops.

02:41:43.746 --> 02:41:45.371
No generals.

02:41:46.081 --> 02:41:49.336
Only those that are left alive
and those that are left...

02:41:49.628 --> 02:41:51.004
...dead.

02:41:51.419 --> 02:41:53.296
I'm glad I won't live to see it.

02:41:53.505 --> 02:41:57.178
REPORTER: Is said you're still
using former Nazis in key positions.

02:41:57.427 --> 02:41:59.597
Despite the denazification policy.

02:41:59.846 --> 02:42:02.891
Well, if I'm supplied
with trained personnel...

02:42:03.100 --> 02:42:04.769
...I'll get rid of the Nazis.

02:42:05.019 --> 02:42:08.982
Until then, I'll use them to keep
the railroads and telephones working.

02:42:09.232 --> 02:42:12.486
After all, didn't most
ordinary Nazis join the Party...

02:42:12.737 --> 02:42:17.074
...in about the same way Americans
become Republicans or Democrats?

02:42:17.450 --> 02:42:18.868
Yes, thas about it.

02:42:22.290 --> 02:42:26.959
You agree that national policy be made
by civilians, not by the military?

02:42:27.546 --> 02:42:30.549
Of course. But the politicians
never let us finish.

02:42:30.800 --> 02:42:33.968
They always stop short and leave us
with another war.

02:42:34.762 --> 02:42:37.097
You thinking about our Russian allies?

02:42:42.063 --> 02:42:46.068
Did you say if you found your army
between the Germans and the Russians...

02:42:46.318 --> 02:42:48.195
...you'd attack in both directions?

02:42:48.443 --> 02:42:50.654
No, I never said that.

02:42:51.448 --> 02:42:53.157
I never said any such thing.

02:42:53.782 --> 02:42:55.368
But I wish I had.

02:43:09.927 --> 02:43:14.015
Sir, there's a call on your line from
supreme headquarters, General Smith.

02:43:19.479 --> 02:43:20.440
Bedell?

02:43:20.982 --> 02:43:22.775
Ike is furious.

02:43:23.024 --> 02:43:27.612
How could you compare Republicans
and Democrats to the Nazi Party?

02:43:27.862 --> 02:43:29.992
And the statement
that you refuse to denazify...

02:43:30.242 --> 02:43:32.995
...has the Russians, the British,
everybody, screaming.

02:43:33.410 --> 02:43:36.124
Well, the hell
with the Mongoloid Russians.

02:43:36.332 --> 02:43:39.377
We've given them Berlin, Prague,
God knows what else.

02:43:39.628 --> 02:43:41.463
They gonna dictate policy too?

02:43:41.713 --> 02:43:43.881
George, don't be a fool.

02:43:44.131 --> 02:43:47.428
The war in Europe is over.
Washington dictates policy.

02:43:47.680 --> 02:43:52.100
The war shouldn't be over. We should
stop pussyfooting about the Russians!

02:43:52.350 --> 02:43:56.231
We'll have to fight them anyway. Why
not do it now, when the army's here?

02:43:56.729 --> 02:44:00.402
Instead of disarming Germans les
get them to help fight the Bolsheviks.

02:44:00.943 --> 02:44:03.362
You better shut up.
This line may be tapped.

02:44:03.614 --> 02:44:05.323
I don't care. I'll tell you...

02:44:05.575 --> 02:44:07.660
...we've been fighting
the wrong people.

02:44:07.909 --> 02:44:11.371
You and I don't have to get involved,
you're so soft about it.

02:44:11.622 --> 02:44:14.919
Leave it to me. In 10 days
I'll have us at war with them...

02:44:15.166 --> 02:44:17.047
...and make it look like their fault!

02:44:17.503 --> 02:44:20.755
George, you're mad.
You're absolutely out of your mind!

02:44:21.007 --> 02:44:22.677
Well, I'm no diplomat.

02:44:22.929 --> 02:44:25.596
I'm a combat soldier.
Thas all they understand.

02:44:25.845 --> 02:44:29.602
Get Ike to give me the word,
and I'll kick them back to Russia!

02:44:39.195 --> 02:44:41.406
Shall I call the artist back, sir?

02:44:43.075 --> 02:44:45.162
Oh, the hell with it.

02:44:46.828 --> 02:44:50.374
Nobody wants to see a picture of me.
I'm mad!

02:44:51.334 --> 02:44:52.878
Don't you know that?

02:45:40.014 --> 02:45:42.976
Field Marshal Montgomery,
his majesty is prepared...

02:45:43.226 --> 02:45:46.689
...to receive the next chief
of the imperial general staff.

02:45:59.703 --> 02:46:01.289
Thank you.

02:46:02.207 --> 02:46:03.791
Thank you.

02:46:04.502 --> 02:46:06.085
Take care of yourself.

02:46:06.295 --> 02:46:07.546
George.

02:46:20.728 --> 02:46:23.605
Well, gentlemen...

02:46:25.318 --> 02:46:28.610
...all good things
must come to an end.

02:46:30.989 --> 02:46:33.826
And the best thing
thas happened to me...

02:46:34.743 --> 02:46:36.329
...in my life...

02:46:38.246 --> 02:46:40.291
...has been...

02:46:43.294 --> 02:46:44.671
...uh...

02:46:45.462 --> 02:46:47.176
...the honor...

02:46:47.675 --> 02:46:50.718
...and privilege...

02:46:52.930 --> 02:46:55.100
...of commanding the 3rd Army.

02:46:57.895 --> 02:46:59.188
Goodbye...

02:47:00.398 --> 02:47:01.983
...and God bless you.

02:47:28.639 --> 02:47:30.556
Brad...

02:47:30.850 --> 02:47:33.394
...they've taken the 3rd Army
away from me.

02:47:33.644 --> 02:47:34.897
I know.

02:47:35.563 --> 02:47:38.482
I thought we could have dinner
together tonight.

02:47:40.194 --> 02:47:43.198
Thank you, Brad.

02:47:43.447 --> 02:47:45.783
Thas damn thoughtful.
I appreciate it.

02:47:53.166 --> 02:47:55.713
Right now, I think I'll take
Willie for a walk.

02:48:03.095 --> 02:48:04.971
George, look out!

02:48:12.482 --> 02:48:14.900
After all I've been through...

02:48:15.149 --> 02:48:17.778
...imagine getting killed
by an oxcart.

02:48:19.238 --> 02:48:23.869
No, Brad, there's only one proper way
for a professional soldier to die.

02:48:24.118 --> 02:48:28.124
Thas from the last bullet
of the last battle of the last war.

02:48:29.209 --> 02:48:32.503
At least the 3rd Army earned its pay.

02:48:33.380 --> 02:48:36.047
In our drive across Europe,
we liberated...

02:48:36.299 --> 02:48:38.343
...12,000 cities and towns...

02:48:38.554 --> 02:48:41.430
...and inflicted a million and a half
enemy casualties.

02:48:41.681 --> 02:48:45.434
I sense from now on, just being
a good soldier won't mean a thing.

02:48:45.684 --> 02:48:50.482
I'm afraid we're gonna have to be
diplomats, administrators, you name it.

02:48:50.732 --> 02:48:52.317
God help us.

02:48:57.533 --> 02:49:00.660
George, I want to say one thing.

02:49:01.995 --> 02:49:04.832
You've done a magnificent job
here in Europe.

02:49:05.543 --> 02:49:07.044
Thas right, George.

02:49:07.835 --> 02:49:12.966
That soldier you slapped did more to
win the war than any other private.

02:49:16.054 --> 02:49:17.763
I'll see you for dinner.

02:49:18.139 --> 02:49:19.640
Six-thirty?

02:49:36.118 --> 02:49:37.912
PATTON:
For over a thousand years...

02:49:38.162 --> 02:49:41.165
...Roman conquerors
returning from the wars...

02:49:41.415 --> 02:49:46.129
...enjoyed the honor of a triumph,
a tumultuous parade.

02:49:46.962 --> 02:49:51.051
In the procession came trumpeters
and musicians and strange animals...

02:49:51.301 --> 02:49:53.220
...from the conquered territories...

02:49:54.096 --> 02:49:58.224
...together with carts laden with
treasure and captured armaments.

02:49:59.476 --> 02:50:03.023
The conqueror rode
in a triumphal chariot...

02:50:03.274 --> 02:50:06.569
...the dazed prisoners
walking in chains before him.

02:50:07.486 --> 02:50:10.240
Sometimes, his children,
robed in white...

02:50:10.490 --> 02:50:14.034
...stood with him in the chariot,
or rode the trace horses.

02:50:15.120 --> 02:50:18.081
A slave stood behind the conqueror...

02:50:18.330 --> 02:50:20.963
...holding a golden crown...

02:50:21.671 --> 02:50:24.505
...and whispering in his ear
a warning...

02:50:25.089 --> 02:50:27.009
...that all glory...

02:50:27.508 --> 02:50:29.346
...is fleeting.

